y:Real property lawyers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of St. George's Order of Victory]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Liberty (Ukraine)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Delaware]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Widener University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Hilal-i-Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]]\n", "name_user": "TJMSmith", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden"}
{"title_page": "Steve Harris (musician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Steve Harris\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = Steve Harris 521.jpg\n| caption = Harris performing in 2008\n| birth_name = Stephen Percy Harris\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1956|03|12}}\n|birth_place =[[Leytonstone]], Essex<!-- Leytonstone was part of Essex in 1956 when Harris was born; it did not join London until 1965 -->, England\n| genre = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument = Bass guitar, keyboards, vocals\n| years_active = 1972\u2013present\n| label = [[EMI]]\n| associated_acts = [[Iron Maiden]], British Lion, [[Lauren Harris]], Smiler, Gypsy's Kiss\n| website = {{url|www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Percy Harris''' (born 12 March 1956) is an English musician, bassist, [[Keyboard instrument|keyboardist]], singer, backing vocalist, primary songwriter and founder of the British [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Iron Maiden]]. He has been the band's only constant member since their inception in 1975 and one of only two to have appeared on all of their albums, the other being guitarist [[Dave Murray (musician)|Dave Murray]].\n\nHarris has a recognisable and popular style of bass playing, particularly the \"gallop\" which can be found on several Iron Maiden recordings, such as the singles \"[[Run to the Hills]]\" and \"[[The Trooper]]\". In addition to his role as the band's bass player, writer and backing vocalist, he has undertaken many other roles for the group, such as producing and co-producing their albums, directing and editing their live videos and performing studio keyboards and synthesizers. He has been cited as one of the greatest heavy metal bassists.\n\nOn 24 September 2012, Harris released his debut solo album, ''[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]]'', which was followed on the 17 January 2020 by ''[[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHarris was born at [[Whipps Cross University Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Waltham Forest]] and grew up in [[Leytonstone]where he was aspiring to be a professional [[Association football|footballer]].{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=15}} Scouted by [[Wally St Pier]], Harris was asked to train for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} After gaining an interest in rock music in his early teens, he realised that he no longer desired to play football professionally.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} \n\nInitially Harris wanted to play drums,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}} but did not have enough space for a drum kit in his house and so decided on the bass instead.<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\">{{cite video|date= 23 November 2004|title=[[The History of Iron Maiden \u2013 Part 1: The Early Days]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> Entirely self-taught,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ironmaiden.com/index.php?categoryid=14&p2_articleid=329 | title = Steve Harris as known by Janick Gers | accessdate = 11 February 2012 | publisher = Iron Maiden Official Website | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100819095537/http://www.ironmaiden.com/index.php?categoryid=14&p2_articleid=329 | archivedate = 19 August 2010 | last = Gers | first = Janick|authorlink=Janick Gers}}</ref> his first bass was a copy of a [[Fender Precision Bass|Fender Precision model]] which cost him \u00a340 in 1971.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}\n\nJust 10 months after he bought his first bass, Harris joined a band, initially known as Influence and later Gypsy's Kiss, featuring Bob Verscoyle (lead vocals), Dave Smith (guitar) and drummer Paul Sears.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=21}} After a short number of gigs at the Cart and Horses pub in Maryland Point, Stratford and the Bridgehouse in Canning Town,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=23}} the band split up and Harris auditioned for a band called Smiler in February 1974.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=24}} In this outfit, Harris began writing his own songs and worked with future Iron Maiden members Dennis Wilcock and [[Doug Sampson]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=25}} but left the band after they refused to play his material, claiming it was too complicated.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=26}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Iron Maiden===\n{{Main|Iron Maiden}}\n\nUpon leaving Smiler, Harris went on to create Iron Maiden on Christmas Day 1975,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=26}} with the band's name being inspired by the film ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1939 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]''.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=28}} Before Iron Maiden signed their contract with [[EMI]] in 1979, Harris worked as an [[Architecture|architectural]] [[technical drawing|draughtsman]] in the [[East End of London]] (he had studied architectural drawing at [[Leyton Sixth Form College]]){{cn|date=April 2019}} until he was made redundant, at which point he undertook a job as a [[street sweeper]].<ref name=\"MH 30th\">{{cite journal | title = Powerslave Driver | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Dave | last = Ling | pages = 31\u201334| id = }}</ref>{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=114}}\n\nSince their inception, Harris has been the band's principal composer and lyricist.<ref name=\"musicradar\"/> His song writing typically showcases his trademark galloping bass patterns, which features heavily in songs such as \"[[The Trooper]]\" and \"[[Run to the Hills]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r9912|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Piece of Mind'' \u2013 Review|accessdate=19 November 2011|first=Steve|last=Huey|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title= 666 of the Best |journal= [[Kerrang!|Kerrang! Legends]] |first= Dom |last= Lawson |issue= 2 |pages= 36\u201337}}</ref> and his progressive rock-influenced time changes.<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\"/><ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> Recently, Harris' songs have become more [[progressive rock|progressive]],<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Good Life | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = September 2006 | first = Malcolm | last = Dome |authorlink=Malcolm Dome| issue = 97 | page = 76| id = }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Maiden: War all the Time | journal = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = September 2006 | first = Malcolm | last = Dome | issue = 157 | pages = 34\u201340 }}</ref> and guitarist [[Adrian Smith]] has commented that Harris now prefers contributing \"lyrics and melodies and arranging\" to other member's songs over writing alone.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Maiden: Adrian Smith | journal = [[Total Guitar]] | date = December 2010 | first = Joel | last = McIver |authorlink=Joel McIver| issue = 208 | pages = 40\u201342 }}</ref> Harris frequently writes lyrics about mythology, history or topics inspired from books and films, reflecting his interests and progressive rock influences.<ref name=\"MH 30th\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title = Maiden at the Movies | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Martin | last = Popoff | pages = 104\u2013105| id = |authorlink=Martin Popoff}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Men | journal = Kerrang! Legends | first = Simon | last = Young | issue = 2 | pages = 90\u201393| id =}}</ref>\n\n===British Lion===\n\nIn September 2012, Harris released his first solo album, ''[[British Lion (album)|British Lion]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Announces First Ever Solo Album 'British Lion' |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223010938/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/|archivedate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Originating with a band, named British Lion, which he managed and wrote with in the early 1990s, Harris kept in touch with its vocalist, Richard Taylor, and guitarist, Graham Leslie, and the album, consisting of 1970s influenced hard rock songs, was written and recorded over a number of years around Iron Maiden's tour schedule.<ref name=\"kerrang lion\">{{cite journal | title = Beyond the Beast | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 15 September 2012 | first = George | last = Garner | issue = 1432 | pages = 22\u201327}}</ref> Speaking to ''[[Kerrang!]]'' in September 2012, Harris stated that he considers the record to be \"more of a side-project\" than a solo album, as he is more \"comfortable in a band environment.\"<ref name=\"kerrang lion\"/>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' in August, Harris stated that he will be releasing more solo albums and hopes to tour with the band in the future.<ref name=\"CRAugust\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ | title = Exclusive: Iron Maiden's Steve Harris talks about his British Lion solo project | accessdate = 8 September 2012 | last = Brannigan | first = Paul | date = 27 August 2012 | magazine = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020112709/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/|archivedate=20 October 2013}}</ref> Harris has taken the outfit on two separate European club tours in 2013 and 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Taking British Lion on the Road \u2013 \"It's Exciting, Going Back to the Roots, And It's Going To Be Fantastic\"|url=http://bravewords.com/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-taking-british-lion-on-the-road-its-exciting-going-back-to-the-roots-and-its-going-to-be-fantastic|work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kielty|first1=Martin|title=Steve Harris confirms British Lion tour|url=http://metalhammer.teamrock.com/news/2014-04-07/steve-harris-confirms-british-lion-tour|website=[[Metal Hammer]]|publisher=TeamRock|accessdate=5 September 2014|date=7 April 2014}}</ref> with an additional tour taking place in 2016. On 2 September 2016, Harris announced that he intends to issue a live album recorded at shows from across the three tours.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kielty|first=Martin|title=Steve Harris details British Lion tour|url=http://teamrock.com/news/2016-09-05/steve-harris-british-lion-european-tour-2016-iron-maiden|work=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|accessdate=9 September 2016|date=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBritish Lion announced in November 2019 that their second album, titled ''The Burning'', will be released on the 17 January 2020.<ref>https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassists-british-lion-to-release-the-burning-album-in-january/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Steve Harris football.jpg|thumb|Harris at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United's]] [[Boleyn Ground]] during Soccer Six 2005.]]\nHarris' eldest daughter, [[Lauren Harris|Lauren]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.monstroentertainment.com/laurenbio.php |title=Bio of Lauren Harris |accessdate=11 April 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070410174403/http://www.monstroentertainment.com/laurenbio.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 10 April 2007 |publisher=Monstroentertainment.com}}</ref> is a singer and supported Iron Maiden with her solo outfit in [[A Matter of Life and Death Tour|2006]] and [[Somewhere Back in Time World Tour|2008]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lane|first=Dan|title=Iron Maiden Kick Off Tour's 2nd Leg|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maiden-kick-off-tours-2nd-leg/|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=22 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723223048/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maiden-kick-off-tours-2nd-leg/|archivedate=23 July 2013}}</ref> In 2008, she released a solo album, entitled ''[[Calm Before the Storm (Lauren Harris album)|Calm Before the Storm]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Iron Maiden Bassist's Daughter To Release Debut Album in May|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassist-s-daughter-to-release-debut-album-in-may/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=20 February 2008}}</ref> and is currently a member of a band called Kingdom of I<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kingdomofimusic.com/About | title = Kingdom of I \u2013 About | accessdate = 25 October 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029194314/http://kingdomofimusic.com/About | archivedate = 29 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> after forming Six Hour Sundown.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.myspace.com/sixhoursundownmusic | title = Six Hour Sundown Myspace | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | publisher = Myspace}}</ref> In addition, Harris' oldest son, George, plays guitar in a band, [[the Raven Age]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The Raven Age Featuring Iron Maiden Bassist's Son George Harris: Toulouse Concert Footage|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/the-raven-age-featuring-iron-maiden-bassists-son-george-harris-toulouse-concert-footage/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=26 July 2014|date=25 July 2014}}</ref> who were the opening act on Iron Maiden's The Book Of Souls World Tour in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lach|first=Stef|title=Raven Age guitarist George Harris chose metal over football|work=[[Team Rock]]|url=http://teamrock.com/news/2016-08-13/raven-age-guitarist-george-harris-chose-metal-over-football|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=13 August 2016}}</ref> and also in the Legacy of the beast tour 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ironmaiden.com/news/article/lotb-2019-dates|title=Legacy Of The Beast Tour 2019 Dates Announced|website=ironmaiden.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>His second-oldest daughter, Kerry, works as a Production Assistant for Iron Maiden<ref>{{cite book | last1 = McMurtrie | first1 = John | authorlink1 = John McMurtrie | title = Iron Maiden: On Board Flight 666 | year = 2011 | edition = 1 | publisher = Orion Books | page = 139 | isbn = 978-1-4091-4136-5}}</ref> while his third-oldest daughter, Faye, is a fashion writer for ''[[HuffPost]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faye Harris MFA Fashion Journalism, Academy of Art University|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/fayeharris-141|website=HuffPost|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Harris was divorced from his wife, Lorraine, whom he met 16 years previously.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} He later said this was \"probably the toughest time I've ever faced,\" and the changes in his personal life are credited with inspiring the mood of the following Iron Maiden album, 1995's ''[[The X Factor (album)|The X Factor]]''.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} Harris has four children with Lorraine: Lauren, Kerry, Faye and George,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} and two children with current partner Emma: Stanley and Maisie.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = From Fear to Eternity Booklet | title-link = From Fear to Eternity (album) | chapter = Iron Maiden Thank- Steve Harris | publisher = [[EMI]]| date = 6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1980s, Harris has owned a Grade II [[listed building]] in Sheering Essex,<ref name=\"Daily Mail property\">{{cite news|last=Hills|first=Suzannah|title=Iron Maiden bassist puts his \u00a37m mansion on the market|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2256729/Iron-Maiden-bassist-puts-7m-mansion-market-complete-garish-murals-busty-women-pub.html?ito=feeds-newsxml|accessdate=4 January 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Mail]]|date=3 January 2013}}</ref> in the grounds of which he built his own recording and editing studio, \"Barnyard\".{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=316}} In November 2012, the nine-acre property was put on sale,<ref>{{cite news|last=Holland|first=Sinead|title=Iron Maiden rocker's Sheering home for sale|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Homes-and-Gardens/Property/Iron-Maiden-rockers-Sheering-home-for-sale-28112012.htm|accessdate=4 January 2013|newspaper=Herts and Essex Observer|date=28 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204033415/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Homes-and-Gardens/Property/Iron-Maiden-rockers-Sheering-home-for-sale-28112012.htm|archivedate=4 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with a spokesman for his estate agent, [[Hamptons International]], stating that \"he now lives between Los Angeles and the Bahamas\".<ref name=\"Daily Mail property\"/>\n\nA keen footballer,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=15}} Harris played for amateur clubs as a child and was later scouted by [[Wally St Pier]] and asked to train for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} of whom he has been a fan since he was 9 years old.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=16}} Although he had aspired to play professionally up to that point, Harris would eventually realise that \"it wasn't really what [he] wanted to do.\"{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} Nevertheless, Harris still plays football regularly with his own team, \"Maidonians\",<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-drummer-to-perform-at-guitar-show-bassist-to-play-at-soccer-tournament/ | title = Iron Maiden Drummer To Perform at Guitar Show, Bassist To Play at Soccer Tournament | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | date = 8 May 2004 | work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref> and still supports West Ham, staying in contact with the club and having their crest on his most-used Precision Bass.<ref name=\"West Ham crest\">{{cite web | url = http://www.footballfancast.com/2010/11/football-blogs/west-hams-top-ten-most-famous-fans/attachment/steve-harris-2 | title = West Ham's Top Ten Most Famous Fans- Steve Harris | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | publisher = Footballfancast.com | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111009092226/http://www.footballfancast.com/2010/11/football-blogs/west-hams-top-ten-most-famous-fans/attachment/steve-harris-2 | archivedate = 9 October 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Harris also plays tennis, and is a photographer.\n\n==Musical style==\n\n===Technique===\nHarris is often considered among the best and most influential [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bassists.<ref name=\"musicradar\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title = Ten of the best bassists\u2026 Ever! | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = January 2000 | quote = #5: Steve Harris \u2013 Iron Maidens ever present backbone, as well as its musical guiding light (Er\u2026 sorry, Bruce)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Bassists of All Time|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/entertainment/top_10_bassists_of_all_time.html|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]|accessdate=11 May 2013|date=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Wins Loudwire's Greatest Metal Bassist Tournament|url=http://loudwire.com/iron-maiden-steve-harris-wins-loudwire-greatest-metal-bassist-tournament/|work=[[Loudwire]]|accessdate=22 October 2013|date=22 October 2013}}</ref> He is most known for his \"galloping\" playing style:<ref name=\"Fendersig\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fender.com/en-GB/series/artist/steve-harris-precision-bass/ | title = Steve Harris Precision Bass\u00ae | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | publisher = [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130122193733/http://www.fender.com/en-GB/series/artist/steve-harris-precision-bass/ | archivedate = 22 January 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> usually an eighth note followed by two sixteenth notes at fast tempo (e.g., \"The Trooper\" and \"Run to the Hills\") or eighth note triplets, which he plays with two fingers, rather than using a [[plectrum]].<ref name=\"musicradar\">{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-25-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/45 | title = The 60 greatest bassists of all time \u2013 16/60, Steve Harris | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | date = 24 September 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131024113236/http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-25-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/45 | archivedate = 24 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://maidenfans.com/2004/harris-is-interested-in-writing-good-songs | title = Harris Is Interested in Writing Good Songs | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | last1 = Bacon | first1 = Tony | last2 = Bradman | first2 = E.E. | date = September 2004 | work = [[Bass Player (magazine)|Bass Player]] | quote = I've always found it easier to play with my fingers; I never learned to play with a pick. I never thought about it as a \"technique\" \u2013 it was just the way I learned to play.}}</ref> Before playing, Harris often chalks his fingers, to make these fast patterns easier to play, as shown on the bonus DVD for the ''[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]'' album.<ref name=\"AMOLADDVD\">{{cite video|date= 28 August 2006|title=[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]|chapter=Documentary|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> Iron Maiden guitarist [[Janick Gers]] has commented that \"Steve taught himself in a way that nobody can really copy it. People say it's like a lead guitar, but it's not. It gives the band a basis and it moves around quite a lot, but it's the tone that he has. Steve has a way of hearing things and a tone that isn't normally associated with a bass, it's more like a rhythm guitar.\"<ref name=\"MH 30th\"/>\n\n===Influences===\nHarris was influenced by the [[progressive rock]] bands of the 1970s, as well as early [[hard rock]] and [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands. His influences include [[Black Sabbath]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassist-talks-about-his-technique-and-influences/ |title=Iron Maiden Bassist Talks About His Technique And Influences |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=25 April 2008 |date=24 September 2004}}</ref> [[Deep Purple]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Emerson, Lake & Palmer]],<ref name=\"NOTBDVD\">{{cite video|date= 4 December 2001|title=[[Classic Albums: Iron Maiden \u2013 The Number of the Beast]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Eagle Rock Entertainment|Eagle Vision]]}}</ref> [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Led Zeppelin]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Pink Floyd]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Thin Lizzy]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=27}} [[UFO (band)|UFO]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=154}} [[Uriah Heep (band)|Uriah Heep]],<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\"/> [[Wishbone Ash]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=27}} and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> Speaking about the early Iron Maiden sound, Steve Harris described the band as using twin-guitar harmonies inspired by Wishbone Ash and Thin Lizzy,<ref name=\"guitar world\">{{cite web | url = http://www.guitarworld.com/iron-maiden-maiden-voyage?page=0%252C2,0 | title = Maiden Voyage | accessdate = 10 October 2011 | date = 3 July 2011 | work = [[Guitar World]] | last = Bienstock | first = Richard}}</ref> complex time and mood changes from Genesis and Jethro Tull,<ref name=\"guitar world\"/> and the dark melodic elements of Black Sabbath, Deep Purple, and Led Zeppelin.<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/>\n\n===Equipment===\nSince Iron Maiden's beginning to the present day, Harris plays a specially-painted [[Fender Precision Bass]], featured on every Iron Maiden album, which has gone through a total of four colour changes since he began using it. Originally white, it was then changed to black prior to the band's [[Iron Maiden (album)|first album]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.guitarworld.com/iron-maiden-maiden-voyage?page=0%252C2,1 | title = Iron Maiden: Maiden Voyage (page 2) | accessdate = 10 October 2011 | date = 3 July 2011 | work = [[Guitar World]] | last = Bienstock | first = Richard}}</ref> followed by blue sparkle and finally white with claret and blue pinstriping with the [[West Ham United F.C.]] crest.<ref name=\"West Ham crest\"/><ref name=\"AMOLADDVD\"/><ref>{{cite video|date= 6 February 2006|title=[[Death on the Road]] | chapter = Life on the Road|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Hammer special\">{{cite journal | title = Hardware | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden, 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Michael | last = Heatley |authorlink=Michael Heatley | pages = 70}}</ref> Harris has had his bass modified to include a mirrored [[Pickguard|scratchplate]], [[Badass (bridges)|Badass]] [[Bridge (instrument)|bridges]] and [[Seymour Duncan]] custom SPB-1 [[Pickup (music technology)|pickups]] and uses his own signature set of [[RotoSound]] flatwound strings.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> In 2009, [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] issued a signature Steve Harris Precision bass,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/exclusive-video-fender-iron-maiden-signature-guitars-206812 | title = Exclusive video: Fender Iron Maiden signature guitars | accessdate = 28 September 2012 | date = 13 May 2009 | publisher = [[MusicRadar]]}}</ref> featuring an alder body, a blue-sparkle finish, mirrored scratchplate, Seymour Duncan SPB-1 pickups and a Badass II bridge.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/gear/all/guitars/electric/bass-guitars/4-string-electric/steve-harris-precision-bass-209621 | title = Fender Steve Harris Precision bass | accessdate = 28 September 2012 | last1 = Bradley | first1 = Simon | last2 = Newell | first2 = Roger | date = 22 June 2009 | publisher = [[MusicRadar]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021840/http://www.musicradar.com//reviews/209621|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Fender released a revised model of the signature bass, which now features a maple body, a white finish with blue pinstripes and the West Ham crest, a Fender High Mass bridge and a Seymour Duncan SPB-4 Steve Harris signature pickup<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris Precision Bass\u00ae|url=http://shop.fender.com/en-US/electric-basses/precision-bass/steve-harris-precision-bass/0141032305.html|publisher=[[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>, with the pickup also being sold separately.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris P-Bass SPB-4|url=http://www.seymourduncan.com/pickup/steve-harris-p-bass|publisher=[[Seymour Duncan]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' reported that he uses eight 4x12\" [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] cabinets with [[Trace Elliot]] amplifiers.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> He also uses four [[Sony]] WRT 27 wireless transmitters, allowing him to be as mobile as possible on stage.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> A diagram of Harris' 2000 bass rig is documented on GuitarGeek.com.<ref>Cooper, Adam (2000). [http://vintage.guitargeek.com/rigview/359/ \"Steve Harris' 2000 Iron Maiden Bass Rig\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817082740/http://vintage.guitargeek.com/rigview/359 |date=17 August 2012 }}. GuitarGeek.Com.</ref>\n\n==Other interests and talents==\nIn addition to playing bass and writing music/lyrics for the band, Steve Harris has taken on numerous other roles, such as:\n* music production/mixing{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=300}}\n* music video directing/editing<ref name=\"visions\"/>\n* live video directing/editing{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=359}}\n* keyboards<ref name=\"Virtual XI\"/>\n* backing vocals\n* string/bass synthesizers{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=258}}\n\nAlthough he performed keyboards on ''[[Seventh Son of a Seventh Son]]'', along with guitarist [[Adrian Smith]], in 1988,<ref name=\"commercial break\">{{cite journal | title = Commercial Break | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Geoff | last = Barton |authorlink=Geoff Barton| pages = 106}}</ref> Harris only began regularly contributing keyboards to Iron Maiden's studio albums from ''[[Virtual XI]]'' onwards.<ref name=\"Virtual XI\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/virtual-xi-mw0000597969/credits | title = ''Virtual XI'' album credits | accessdate = 27 September 2011 | publisher = [[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> Until ''Virtual XI'', Michael Kenney, Harris' bass technician, had provided the keyboards from 1990's ''[[No Prayer for the Dying]]'' onwards, and still does so live and acts as a supervisor in the studio.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.keyboardmag.com/article/Michael-Kenney---the-Man-Behind-the-Maiden/2314 | title = Michael Kenney \u2013 the Man Behind the Maiden | last = Gennet | first = Robbie | date = 3 October 2010 | accessdate = 19 April 2012 | magazine = [[Keyboard Magazine]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130516191252/http://www.keyboardmag.com/article/Michael-Kenney---the-Man-Behind-the-Maiden/2314 | archivedate = 16 May 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ironmaiden.com/the-final-frontier---recording-diary-by-kevin-shirley.html| title = Final Frontier recording diary | accessdate = 27 September 2011 | publisher = ironmaiden.com | quote = Michael Kenney set up the keys and Steve poked away at them, hunting for the melodies running around his head like a chicken pecking the ground.|last=Shirley|first=Kevin|authorlink=Kevin Shirley}}</ref> Along with Smith and guitarist [[Dave Murray (musician)|Dave Murray]], Harris experimented with synthesizers on the ''[[Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album)|Somewhere in Time]]'' and ''Seventh Son of a Seventh Son'' albums,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=158}} using [[Synthesizer#Synth bass|bass synth]] on ''Somewhere in Time'',<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Somewhere in Time Booklet | title-link = Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album) | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 29 September 1986}}</ref> and performing \"[[Synthesizer#Synth pad|string synth]]\" keyboards on ''Seventh Son of a Seventh Son''.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Seventh Son of a Seventh Son Booklet | title-link = Seventh Son of a Seventh Son | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 11 April 1988}}</ref>\n\nSteve Harris is also known for playing an increasing role in [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] the band's albums and produced most of their 1990's output,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=300}} with recording taking place at a studio he owned at the time, located in a barn on his property,<ref name=\"CR 2000\">{{cite journal | title = The Wicked Man| journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = June 2000 | issue = 15 | pages = 36\u201343 |last=Berelian|first=Essi}}</ref> named \"Barnyard Studios\".{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=316}} Since 2000's ''Brave New World'', at [[Bruce Dickinson]]'s insistence, the band did not record again at Barnyard, which Dickinson claims had limitations due to its size, and hired [[Kevin Shirley]],<ref name=\"CR 2000\"/> with whom Harris co-produces.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = The Final Frontier Booklet | title-link = The Final Frontier | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 16 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nHarris also directs and edits many of the band's live videos, beginning with ''[[Maiden England]]'' in 1989.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=275}} Although not intending to himself, Harris edited the ''[[Rock in Rio (album)|Rock in Rio]]'' DVD as he was unsatisfied with the results produced by the band's hired production crew.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=358}} In undertaking the project, Harris had to teach himself how to use digital editing software with equipment he had installed in Barnyard Studios,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=359}} and went on to edit Iron Maiden's next DVD, ''[[Death on the Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-harris-mn0000035720/credits|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> On top of this, he has contributed to the production of thirteen of the band's music videos, with \"[[Infinite Dreams]]\", \"[[Holy Smoke (song)|Holy Smoke]]\", \"Tailgunner\" and \"[[Bring Your Daughter... to the Slaughter]]\" being directed and edited by Harris alone.<ref name=\"visions\">{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Visions of the Beast DVD cover | title-link = Visions of the Beast | chapter = Video credits | publisher = [[EMI]]| date = 2 June 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Steve-Harris-2008.jpg|thumb|right|Steve Harris 2008]]\n{{col-float|width=25em}}\n\n===Iron Maiden===\n{{Main|Iron Maiden discography}}\n*''[[Iron Maiden (album)|Iron Maiden]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Killers (Iron Maiden album)|Killers]]'' (1981)\n*''[[The Number of the Beast (album)|The Number of the Beast]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Piece of Mind]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Powerslave]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album)|Somewhere in Time]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Seventh Son of a Seventh Son]]'' (1988)\n*''[[No Prayer for the Dying]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Fear of the Dark (Iron Maiden album)|Fear of the Dark]]'' (1992)\n*''[[The X Factor (album)|The X Factor]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Virtual XI]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Brave New World (Iron Maiden album)|Brave New World]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Dance of Death (album)|Dance of Death]]'' (2003)\n*''[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Final Frontier]]'' (2010)\n*''[[The Book of Souls]]'' (2015)\n{{col-float-break|width=25em}}\n\n===Steve Harris' British Lion===\n*''[[British Lion (album)|British Lion]]'' (2012)\n*''[[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]'' (2020)\n\n===Lauren Harris===\n*''[[Calm Before the Storm (Lauren Harris album)|Calm Before the Storm]]'' (2008)\n\n===Deeds===\n*''Blown'' (Producer, 2002)<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/deeds-set-tentative-release-date-for-blown/ | title = Deeds Set Tentative Release Date For ''Blown'' | accessdate = 6 September 2016 | date = 23 May 2002 | work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref>\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Literature ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Wall\n|first = Mick\n|authorlink=Mick Wall\n|title = Iron Maiden: Run to the Hills, the Authorised Biography\n|edition = third\n|publisher = Sanctuary Publishing\n|year = 2004\n|isbn = 1-86074-542-3\n|ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Steve Harris}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0000035720|title=Steve Harris}}\n* {{imdb name|1064240|Steve Harris}}\n\n{{IronMaiden}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iron Maiden members]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:People from Leytonstone]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Waysted members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Steve Harris\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = Steve Harris 521.jpg\n| caption = Harris performing in 2008\n| birth_name = Stephen Percy Harris\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1956|03|12}}\n|birth_place =[[Leytonstone]], Essex<!-- Leytonstone was part of Essex in 1956 when Harris was born; it did not join London until 1965 -->, England\n| genre = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument = Bass guitar, keyboards, vocals\n| years_active = 1972\u2013present\n| label = [[EMI]]\n| associated_acts = [[Iron Maiden]], British Lion, [[Lauren Harris]], Smiler, Gypsy's Kiss\n| website = {{url|www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Percy Harris''' (born 12 March 1956) is an English musician, bassist, [[Keyboard instrument|keyboardist]], singer, backing vocalist, primary songwriter and founder of the British [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Iron Maiden]]. He has been the band's only constant member since their inception in 1975 and one of only two to have appeared on all of their albums, the other being guitarist [[Dave Murray (musician)|Dave Murray]].\n\nHarris has a recognisable and popular style of bass playing, particularly the \"gallop\" which can be found on several Iron Maiden recordings, such as the singles \"[[Run to the Hills]]\" and \"[[The Trooper]]\". In addition to his role as the band's bass player, writer and backing vocalist, he has undertaken many other roles for the group, such as producing and co-producing their albums, directing and editing their live videos and performing studio keyboards and synthesizers. He has been cited as one of the greatest heavy metal bassists.\n\nOn 24 September 2012, Harris released his debut solo album, ''[[British Lion (album)|British Lion]]'', which was followed on the 17 January 2020 by ''[[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHarris was born at [[Whipps Cross University Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Waltham Forest]] and grew up in [[Leytonstone]where he was aspiring to be a professional [[Association football|footballer]].{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=15}} Scouted by [[Wally St Pier]], Harris was asked to train for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} After gaining an interest in rock music in his early teens, he realised that he no longer desired to play football professionally.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} \n\nInitially Harris wanted to play drums,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}} but did not have enough space for a drum kit in his house and so decided on the bass instead.<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\">{{cite video|date= 23 November 2004|title=[[The History of Iron Maiden \u2013 Part 1: The Early Days]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> Entirely self-taught,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ironmaiden.com/index.php?categoryid=14&p2_articleid=329 | title = Steve Harris as known by Janick Gers | accessdate = 11 February 2012 | publisher = Iron Maiden Official Website | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100819095537/http://www.ironmaiden.com/index.php?categoryid=14&p2_articleid=329 | archivedate = 19 August 2010 | last = Gers | first = Janick|authorlink=Janick Gers}}</ref> his first bass was a copy of a [[Fender Precision Bass|Fender Precision model]] which cost him \u00a340 in 1971.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}\n\nJust 10 months after he bought his first bass, Harris joined a band, initially known as Influence and later Gypsy's Kiss, featuring Bob Verscoyle (lead vocals), Dave Smith (guitar) and drummer Paul Sears.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=21}} After a short number of gigs at the Cart and Horses pub in Maryland Point, Stratford and the Bridgehouse in Canning Town,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=23}} the band split up and Harris auditioned for a band called Smiler in February 1974.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=24}} In this outfit, Harris began writing his own songs and worked with future Iron Maiden members Dennis Wilcock and [[Doug Sampson]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=25}} but left the band after they refused to play his material, claiming it was too complicated.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=26}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Iron Maiden===\n{{Main|Iron Maiden}}\n\nUpon leaving Smiler, Harris went on to create Iron Maiden on Christmas Day 1975,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=26}} with the band's name being inspired by the film ''[[The Man in the Iron Mask (1939 film)|The Man in the Iron Mask]]''.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=28}} Before Iron Maiden signed their contract with [[EMI]] in 1979, Harris worked as an [[Architecture|architectural]] [[technical drawing|draughtsman]] in the [[East End of London]] (he had studied architectural drawing at [[Leyton Sixth Form College]]){{cn|date=April 2019}} until he was made redundant, at which point he undertook a job as a [[street sweeper]].<ref name=\"MH 30th\">{{cite journal | title = Powerslave Driver | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Dave | last = Ling | pages = 31\u201334| id = }}</ref>{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=114}}\n\nSince their inception, Harris has been the band's principal composer and lyricist.<ref name=\"musicradar\"/> His song writing typically showcases his trademark galloping bass patterns, which features heavily in songs such as \"[[The Trooper]]\" and \"[[Run to the Hills]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r9912|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Piece of Mind'' \u2013 Review|accessdate=19 November 2011|first=Steve|last=Huey|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title= 666 of the Best |journal= [[Kerrang!|Kerrang! Legends]] |first= Dom |last= Lawson |issue= 2 |pages= 36\u201337}}</ref> and his progressive rock-influenced time changes.<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\"/><ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> Recently, Harris' songs have become more [[progressive rock|progressive]],<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Good Life | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = September 2006 | first = Malcolm | last = Dome |authorlink=Malcolm Dome| issue = 97 | page = 76| id = }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Maiden: War all the Time | journal = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = September 2006 | first = Malcolm | last = Dome | issue = 157 | pages = 34\u201340 }}</ref> and guitarist [[Adrian Smith]] has commented that Harris now prefers contributing \"lyrics and melodies and arranging\" to other member's songs over writing alone.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Maiden: Adrian Smith | journal = [[Total Guitar]] | date = December 2010 | first = Joel | last = McIver |authorlink=Joel McIver| issue = 208 | pages = 40\u201342 }}</ref> Harris frequently writes lyrics about mythology, history or topics inspired from books and films, reflecting his interests and progressive rock influences.<ref name=\"MH 30th\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title = Maiden at the Movies | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Martin | last = Popoff | pages = 104\u2013105| id = |authorlink=Martin Popoff}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Iron Men | journal = Kerrang! Legends | first = Simon | last = Young | issue = 2 | pages = 90\u201393| id =}}</ref>\n\n===British Lion===\n\nIn September 2012, Harris released his first solo album, ''[[British Lion (album)|British Lion]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Announces First Ever Solo Album 'British Lion' |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223010938/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/|archivedate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Originating with a band, named British Lion, which he managed and wrote with in the early 1990s, Harris kept in touch with its vocalist, Richard Taylor, and guitarist, Graham Leslie, and the album, consisting of 1970s influenced hard rock songs, was written and recorded over a number of years around Iron Maiden's tour schedule.<ref name=\"kerrang lion\">{{cite journal | title = Beyond the Beast | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 15 September 2012 | first = George | last = Garner | issue = 1432 | pages = 22\u201327}}</ref> Speaking to ''[[Kerrang!]]'' in September 2012, Harris stated that he considers the record to be \"more of a side-project\" than a solo album, as he is more \"comfortable in a band environment.\"<ref name=\"kerrang lion\"/>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' in August, Harris stated that he will be releasing more solo albums and hopes to tour with the band in the future.<ref name=\"CRAugust\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ | title = Exclusive: Iron Maiden's Steve Harris talks about his British Lion solo project | accessdate = 8 September 2012 | last = Brannigan | first = Paul | date = 27 August 2012 | magazine = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020112709/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/|archivedate=20 October 2013}}</ref> Harris has taken the outfit on two separate European club tours in 2013 and 2014,<ref>{{cite web|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Taking British Lion on the Road \u2013 \"It's Exciting, Going Back to the Roots, And It's Going To Be Fantastic\"|url=http://bravewords.com/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-taking-british-lion-on-the-road-its-exciting-going-back-to-the-roots-and-its-going-to-be-fantastic|work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kielty|first1=Martin|title=Steve Harris confirms British Lion tour|url=http://metalhammer.teamrock.com/news/2014-04-07/steve-harris-confirms-british-lion-tour|website=[[Metal Hammer]]|publisher=TeamRock|accessdate=5 September 2014|date=7 April 2014}}</ref> with an additional tour taking place in 2016. On 2 September 2016, Harris announced that he intends to issue a live album recorded at shows from across the three tours.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kielty|first=Martin|title=Steve Harris details British Lion tour|url=http://teamrock.com/news/2016-09-05/steve-harris-british-lion-european-tour-2016-iron-maiden|work=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|accessdate=9 September 2016|date=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBritish Lion announced in November 2019 that their second album, titled ''The Burning'', will be released on the 17 January 2020.<ref>https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassists-british-lion-to-release-the-burning-album-in-january/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Steve Harris football.jpg|thumb|Harris at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United's]] [[Boleyn Ground]] during Soccer Six 2005.]]\nHarris' eldest daughter, [[Lauren Harris|Lauren]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.monstroentertainment.com/laurenbio.php |title=Bio of Lauren Harris |accessdate=11 April 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070410174403/http://www.monstroentertainment.com/laurenbio.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 10 April 2007 |publisher=Monstroentertainment.com}}</ref> is a singer and supported Iron Maiden with her solo outfit in [[A Matter of Life and Death Tour|2006]] and [[Somewhere Back in Time World Tour|2008]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lane|first=Dan|title=Iron Maiden Kick Off Tour's 2nd Leg|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maiden-kick-off-tours-2nd-leg/|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=22 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723223048/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maiden-kick-off-tours-2nd-leg/|archivedate=23 July 2013}}</ref> In 2008, she released a solo album, entitled ''[[Calm Before the Storm (Lauren Harris album)|Calm Before the Storm]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Iron Maiden Bassist's Daughter To Release Debut Album in May|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassist-s-daughter-to-release-debut-album-in-may/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=20 February 2008}}</ref> and is currently a member of a band called Kingdom of I<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kingdomofimusic.com/About | title = Kingdom of I \u2013 About | accessdate = 25 October 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029194314/http://kingdomofimusic.com/About | archivedate = 29 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> after forming Six Hour Sundown.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.myspace.com/sixhoursundownmusic | title = Six Hour Sundown Myspace | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | publisher = Myspace}}</ref> In addition, Harris' oldest son, George, plays guitar in a band, [[the Raven Age]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The Raven Age Featuring Iron Maiden Bassist's Son George Harris: Toulouse Concert Footage|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/the-raven-age-featuring-iron-maiden-bassists-son-george-harris-toulouse-concert-footage/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=26 July 2014|date=25 July 2014}}</ref> who were the opening act on Iron Maiden's The Book Of Souls World Tour in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lach|first=Stef|title=Raven Age guitarist George Harris chose metal over football|work=[[Team Rock]]|url=http://teamrock.com/news/2016-08-13/raven-age-guitarist-george-harris-chose-metal-over-football|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=13 August 2016}}</ref> and also in the Legacy of the beast tour 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ironmaiden.com/news/article/lotb-2019-dates|title=Legacy Of The Beast Tour 2019 Dates Announced|website=ironmaiden.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>His second-oldest daughter, Kerry, works as a Production Assistant for Iron Maiden<ref>{{cite book | last1 = McMurtrie | first1 = John | authorlink1 = John McMurtrie | title = Iron Maiden: On Board Flight 666 | year = 2011 | edition = 1 | publisher = Orion Books | page = 139 | isbn = 978-1-4091-4136-5}}</ref> while his third-oldest daughter, Faye, is a fashion writer for ''[[HuffPost]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faye Harris MFA Fashion Journalism, Academy of Art University|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/fayeharris-141|website=HuffPost|accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Harris was divorced from his wife, Lorraine, whom he met 16 years previously.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} He later said this was \"probably the toughest time I've ever faced,\" and the changes in his personal life are credited with inspiring the mood of the following Iron Maiden album, 1995's ''[[The X Factor (album)|The X Factor]]''.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} Harris has four children with Lorraine: Lauren, Kerry, Faye and George,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=311}} and two children with current partner Emma: Stanley and Maisie.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = From Fear to Eternity Booklet | title-link = From Fear to Eternity (album) | chapter = Iron Maiden Thank- Steve Harris | publisher = [[EMI]]| date = 6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1980s, Harris has owned a Grade II [[listed building]] in Sheering Essex,<ref name=\"Daily Mail property\">{{cite news|last=Hills|first=Suzannah|title=Iron Maiden bassist puts his \u00a37m mansion on the market|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2256729/Iron-Maiden-bassist-puts-7m-mansion-market-complete-garish-murals-busty-women-pub.html?ito=feeds-newsxml|accessdate=4 January 2013|newspaper=[[The Daily Mail]]|date=3 January 2013}}</ref> in the grounds of which he built his own recording and editing studio, \"Barnyard\".{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=316}} In November 2012, the nine-acre property was put on sale,<ref>{{cite news|last=Holland|first=Sinead|title=Iron Maiden rocker's Sheering home for sale|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Homes-and-Gardens/Property/Iron-Maiden-rockers-Sheering-home-for-sale-28112012.htm|accessdate=4 January 2013|newspaper=Herts and Essex Observer|date=28 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204033415/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Homes-and-Gardens/Property/Iron-Maiden-rockers-Sheering-home-for-sale-28112012.htm|archivedate=4 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with a spokesman for his estate agent, [[Hamptons International]], stating that \"he now lives between Los Angeles and the Bahamas\".<ref name=\"Daily Mail property\"/>\n\nA keen footballer,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=15}} Harris played for amateur clubs as a child and was later scouted by [[Wally St Pier]] and asked to train for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} of whom he has been a fan since he was 9 years old.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=16}} Although he had aspired to play professionally up to that point, Harris would eventually realise that \"it wasn't really what [he] wanted to do.\"{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=17}} Nevertheless, Harris still plays football regularly with his own team, \"Maidonians\",<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-drummer-to-perform-at-guitar-show-bassist-to-play-at-soccer-tournament/ | title = Iron Maiden Drummer To Perform at Guitar Show, Bassist To Play at Soccer Tournament | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | date = 8 May 2004 | work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref> and still supports West Ham, staying in contact with the club and having their crest on his most-used Precision Bass.<ref name=\"West Ham crest\">{{cite web | url = http://www.footballfancast.com/2010/11/football-blogs/west-hams-top-ten-most-famous-fans/attachment/steve-harris-2 | title = West Ham's Top Ten Most Famous Fans- Steve Harris | accessdate = 30 August 2011 | publisher = Footballfancast.com | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111009092226/http://www.footballfancast.com/2010/11/football-blogs/west-hams-top-ten-most-famous-fans/attachment/steve-harris-2 | archivedate = 9 October 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Harris also plays tennis, and is a photographer.\n\n==Musical style==\n\n===Technique===\nHarris is often considered among the best and most influential [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bassists.<ref name=\"musicradar\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title = Ten of the best bassists\u2026 Ever! | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = January 2000 | quote = #5: Steve Harris \u2013 Iron Maidens ever present backbone, as well as its musical guiding light (Er\u2026 sorry, Bruce)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Bassists of All Time|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/entertainment/top_10_bassists_of_all_time.html|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]|accessdate=11 May 2013|date=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hartmann|first=Graham|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Wins Loudwire's Greatest Metal Bassist Tournament|url=http://loudwire.com/iron-maiden-steve-harris-wins-loudwire-greatest-metal-bassist-tournament/|work=[[Loudwire]]|accessdate=22 October 2013|date=22 October 2013}}</ref> He is most known for his \"galloping\" playing style:<ref name=\"Fendersig\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fender.com/en-GB/series/artist/steve-harris-precision-bass/ | title = Steve Harris Precision Bass\u00ae | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | publisher = [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130122193733/http://www.fender.com/en-GB/series/artist/steve-harris-precision-bass/ | archivedate = 22 January 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> usually an eighth note followed by two sixteenth notes at fast tempo (e.g., \"The Trooper\" and \"Run to the Hills\") or eighth note triplets, which he plays with two fingers, rather than using a [[plectrum]].<ref name=\"musicradar\">{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-25-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/45 | title = The 60 greatest bassists of all time \u2013 16/60, Steve Harris | publisher = [[MusicRadar]] | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | date = 24 September 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131024113236/http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-25-greatest-bassists-of-all-time-279007/45 | archivedate = 24 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://maidenfans.com/2004/harris-is-interested-in-writing-good-songs | title = Harris Is Interested in Writing Good Songs | accessdate = 21 September 2011 | last1 = Bacon | first1 = Tony | last2 = Bradman | first2 = E.E. | date = September 2004 | work = [[Bass Player (magazine)|Bass Player]] | quote = I've always found it easier to play with my fingers; I never learned to play with a pick. I never thought about it as a \"technique\" \u2013 it was just the way I learned to play.}}</ref> Before playing, Harris often chalks his fingers, to make these fast patterns easier to play, as shown on the bonus DVD for the ''[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]'' album.<ref name=\"AMOLADDVD\">{{cite video|date= 28 August 2006|title=[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]|chapter=Documentary|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> Iron Maiden guitarist [[Janick Gers]] has commented that \"Steve taught himself in a way that nobody can really copy it. People say it's like a lead guitar, but it's not. It gives the band a basis and it moves around quite a lot, but it's the tone that he has. Steve has a way of hearing things and a tone that isn't normally associated with a bass, it's more like a rhythm guitar.\"<ref name=\"MH 30th\"/>\n\n===Influences===\nHarris was influenced by the [[progressive rock]] bands of the 1970s, as well as early [[hard rock]] and [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands. His influences include [[Black Sabbath]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/iron-maiden-bassist-talks-about-his-technique-and-influences/ |title=Iron Maiden Bassist Talks About His Technique And Influences |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |accessdate=25 April 2008 |date=24 September 2004}}</ref> [[Deep Purple]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Emerson, Lake & Palmer]],<ref name=\"NOTBDVD\">{{cite video|date= 4 December 2001|title=[[Classic Albums: Iron Maiden \u2013 The Number of the Beast]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Eagle Rock Entertainment|Eagle Vision]]}}</ref> [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=20}}<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Led Zeppelin]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Pink Floyd]],<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> [[Thin Lizzy]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=27}} [[UFO (band)|UFO]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=154}} [[Uriah Heep (band)|Uriah Heep]],<ref name=\"earlydaysdvd\"/> [[Wishbone Ash]],{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=27}} and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/> Speaking about the early Iron Maiden sound, Steve Harris described the band as using twin-guitar harmonies inspired by Wishbone Ash and Thin Lizzy,<ref name=\"guitar world\">{{cite web | url = http://www.guitarworld.com/iron-maiden-maiden-voyage?page=0%252C2,0 | title = Maiden Voyage | accessdate = 10 October 2011 | date = 3 July 2011 | work = [[Guitar World]] | last = Bienstock | first = Richard}}</ref> complex time and mood changes from Genesis and Jethro Tull,<ref name=\"guitar world\"/> and the dark melodic elements of Black Sabbath, Deep Purple, and Led Zeppelin.<ref name=\"Blabbermouth Iron Maiden\"/>\n\n===Equipment===\nSince Iron Maiden's beginning to the present day, Harris plays a specially-painted [[Fender Precision Bass]], featured on every Iron Maiden album, which has gone through a total of four colour changes since he began using it. Originally white, it was then changed to black prior to the band's [[Iron Maiden (album)|first album]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.guitarworld.com/iron-maiden-maiden-voyage?page=0%252C2,1 | title = Iron Maiden: Maiden Voyage (page 2) | accessdate = 10 October 2011 | date = 3 July 2011 | work = [[Guitar World]] | last = Bienstock | first = Richard}}</ref> followed by blue sparkle and finally white with claret and blue pinstriping with the [[West Ham United F.C.]] crest.<ref name=\"West Ham crest\"/><ref name=\"AMOLADDVD\"/><ref>{{cite video|date= 6 February 2006|title=[[Death on the Road]] | chapter = Life on the Road|medium=DVD|publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Hammer special\">{{cite journal | title = Hardware | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden, 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Michael | last = Heatley |authorlink=Michael Heatley | pages = 70}}</ref> Harris has had his bass modified to include a mirrored [[Pickguard|scratchplate]], [[Badass (bridges)|Badass]] [[Bridge (instrument)|bridges]] and [[Seymour Duncan]] custom SPB-1 [[Pickup (music technology)|pickups]] and uses his own signature set of [[RotoSound]] flatwound strings.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> In 2009, [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] issued a signature Steve Harris Precision bass,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/exclusive-video-fender-iron-maiden-signature-guitars-206812 | title = Exclusive video: Fender Iron Maiden signature guitars | accessdate = 28 September 2012 | date = 13 May 2009 | publisher = [[MusicRadar]]}}</ref> featuring an alder body, a blue-sparkle finish, mirrored scratchplate, Seymour Duncan SPB-1 pickups and a Badass II bridge.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.musicradar.com/gear/all/guitars/electric/bass-guitars/4-string-electric/steve-harris-precision-bass-209621 | title = Fender Steve Harris Precision bass | accessdate = 28 September 2012 | last1 = Bradley | first1 = Simon | last2 = Newell | first2 = Roger | date = 22 June 2009 | publisher = [[MusicRadar]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021840/http://www.musicradar.com//reviews/209621|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Fender released a revised model of the signature bass, which now features a maple body, a white finish with blue pinstripes and the West Ham crest, a Fender High Mass bridge and a Seymour Duncan SPB-4 Steve Harris signature pickup<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris Precision Bass\u00ae|url=http://shop.fender.com/en-US/electric-basses/precision-bass/steve-harris-precision-bass/0141032305.html|publisher=[[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>, with the pickup also being sold separately.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris P-Bass SPB-4|url=http://www.seymourduncan.com/pickup/steve-harris-p-bass|publisher=[[Seymour Duncan]]|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' reported that he uses eight 4x12\" [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] cabinets with [[Trace Elliot]] amplifiers.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> He also uses four [[Sony]] WRT 27 wireless transmitters, allowing him to be as mobile as possible on stage.<ref name=\"Hammer special\"/> A diagram of Harris' 2000 bass rig is documented on GuitarGeek.com.<ref>Cooper, Adam (2000). [http://vintage.guitargeek.com/rigview/359/ \"Steve Harris' 2000 Iron Maiden Bass Rig\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817082740/http://vintage.guitargeek.com/rigview/359 |date=17 August 2012 }}. GuitarGeek.Com.</ref>\n\n==Other interests and talents==\nIn addition to playing bass and writing music/lyrics for the band, Steve Harris has taken on numerous other roles, such as:\n* music production/mixing{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=300}}\n* music video directing/editing<ref name=\"visions\"/>\n* live video directing/editing{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=359}}\n* keyboards<ref name=\"Virtual XI\"/>\n* backing vocals\n* string/bass synthesizers{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=258}}\n\nAlthough he performed keyboards on ''[[Seventh Son of a Seventh Son]]'', along with guitarist [[Adrian Smith]], in 1988,<ref name=\"commercial break\">{{cite journal | title = Commercial Break | journal = Metal Hammer Presents: Iron Maiden 30 Years of Metal Mayhem | year = 2005 | first = Geoff | last = Barton |authorlink=Geoff Barton| pages = 106}}</ref> Harris only began regularly contributing keyboards to Iron Maiden's studio albums from ''[[Virtual XI]]'' onwards.<ref name=\"Virtual XI\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/virtual-xi-mw0000597969/credits | title = ''Virtual XI'' album credits | accessdate = 27 September 2011 | publisher = [[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> Until ''Virtual XI'', Michael Kenney, Harris' bass technician, had provided the keyboards from 1990's ''[[No Prayer for the Dying]]'' onwards, and still does so live and acts as a supervisor in the studio.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.keyboardmag.com/article/Michael-Kenney---the-Man-Behind-the-Maiden/2314 | title = Michael Kenney \u2013 the Man Behind the Maiden | last = Gennet | first = Robbie | date = 3 October 2010 | accessdate = 19 April 2012 | magazine = [[Keyboard Magazine]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130516191252/http://www.keyboardmag.com/article/Michael-Kenney---the-Man-Behind-the-Maiden/2314 | archivedate = 16 May 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ironmaiden.com/the-final-frontier---recording-diary-by-kevin-shirley.html| title = Final Frontier recording diary | accessdate = 27 September 2011 | publisher = ironmaiden.com | quote = Michael Kenney set up the keys and Steve poked away at them, hunting for the melodies running around his head like a chicken pecking the ground.|last=Shirley|first=Kevin|authorlink=Kevin Shirley}}</ref> Along with Smith and guitarist [[Dave Murray (musician)|Dave Murray]], Harris experimented with synthesizers on the ''[[Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album)|Somewhere in Time]]'' and ''Seventh Son of a Seventh Son'' albums,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=158}} using [[Synthesizer#Synth bass|bass synth]] on ''Somewhere in Time'',<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Somewhere in Time Booklet | title-link = Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album) | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 29 September 1986}}</ref> and performing \"[[Synthesizer#Synth pad|string synth]]\" keyboards on ''Seventh Son of a Seventh Son''.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Seventh Son of a Seventh Son Booklet | title-link = Seventh Son of a Seventh Son | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 11 April 1988}}</ref>\n\nSteve Harris is also known for playing an increasing role in [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]] the band's albums and produced most of their 1990's output,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=300}} with recording taking place at a studio he owned at the time, located in a barn on his property,<ref name=\"CR 2000\">{{cite journal | title = The Wicked Man| journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = June 2000 | issue = 15 | pages = 36\u201343 |last=Berelian|first=Essi}}</ref> named \"Barnyard Studios\".{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=316}} Since 2000's ''Brave New World'', at [[Bruce Dickinson]]'s insistence, the band did not record again at Barnyard, which Dickinson claims had limitations due to its size, and hired [[Kevin Shirley]],<ref name=\"CR 2000\"/> with whom Harris co-produces.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = The Final Frontier Booklet | title-link = The Final Frontier | chapter = Album credits | publisher = [[EMI]] | date = 16 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nHarris also directs and edits many of the band's live videos, beginning with ''[[Maiden England]]'' in 1989.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=275}} Although not intending to himself, Harris edited the ''[[Rock in Rio (album)|Rock in Rio]]'' DVD as he was unsatisfied with the results produced by the band's hired production crew.{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=358}} In undertaking the project, Harris had to teach himself how to use digital editing software with equipment he had installed in Barnyard Studios,{{sfn|Wall|2004|p=359}} and went on to edit Iron Maiden's next DVD, ''[[Death on the Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Harris credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/steve-harris-mn0000035720/credits|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref> On top of this, he has contributed to the production of thirteen of the band's music videos, with \"[[Infinite Dreams]]\", \"[[Holy Smoke (song)|Holy Smoke]]\", \"Tailgunner\" and \"[[Bring Your Daughter... to the Slaughter]]\" being directed and edited by Harris alone.<ref name=\"visions\">{{cite book | last1 = Iron Maiden | title = Visions of the Beast DVD cover | title-link = Visions of the Beast | chapter = Video credits | publisher = [[EMI]]| date = 2 June 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Steve-Harris-2008.jpg|thumb|right|Steve Harris 2008]]\n{{col-float|width=25em}}\n\n===Iron Maiden===\n{{Main|Iron Maiden discography}}\n*''[[Iron Maiden (album)|Iron Maiden]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Killers (Iron Maiden album)|Killers]]'' (1981)\n*''[[The Number of the Beast (album)|The Number of the Beast]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Piece of Mind]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Powerslave]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Somewhere in Time (Iron Maiden album)|Somewhere in Time]]'' (1986)\n*''[[Seventh Son of a Seventh Son]]'' (1988)\n*''[[No Prayer for the Dying]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Fear of the Dark (Iron Maiden album)|Fear of the Dark]]'' (1992)\n*''[[The X Factor (album)|The X Factor]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Virtual XI]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Brave New World (Iron Maiden album)|Brave New World]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Dance of Death (album)|Dance of Death]]'' (2003)\n*''[[A Matter of Life and Death (album)|A Matter of Life and Death]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Final Frontier]]'' (2010)\n*''[[The Book of Souls]]'' (2015)\n{{col-float-break|width=25em}}\n\n===Steve Harris' British Lion===\n*''[[British Lion (album)|British Lion]]'' (2012)\n*''[[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]'' (2020)\n\n===Lauren Harris===\n*''[[Calm Before the Storm (Lauren Harris album)|Calm Before the Storm]]'' (2008)\n\n===Deeds===\n*''Blown'' (Producer, 2002)<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/deeds-set-tentative-release-date-for-blown/ | title = Deeds Set Tentative Release Date For ''Blown'' | accessdate = 6 September 2016 | date = 23 May 2002 | work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref>\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Literature ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Wall\n|first = Mick\n|authorlink=Mick Wall\n|title = Iron Maiden: Run to the Hills, the Authorised Biography\n|edition = third\n|publisher = Sanctuary Publishing\n|year = 2004\n|isbn = 1-86074-542-3\n|ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Steve Harris}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0000035720|title=Steve Harris}}\n* {{imdb name|1064240|Steve Harris}}\n\n{{IronMaiden}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iron Maiden members]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:People from Leytonstone]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Waysted members]]\n", "name_user": "MichaelSharman", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have added the link to the Steve Harris British Lion Band Wikipedia page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Harris_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Paul Merage", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Paul Merage\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1934}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| birth_name  = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| residence   = [[Newport Beach, California]]\n| nationality = United States\n| education   = B.A. and M.B.A. [[UC Berkeley]]\n| alma mater  = [[Hope College]]\n| occupation  = Businessman\n| known_for   = Co-founder of [[Chef America Inc.]]\n| networth    = $5.0 billion (2011)\n| spouse      = Lily Merage\n| parents     = \n| children    = Michelle Janavs\n| family      = David Merage (brother)\n| website     = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Merage''' (born 1934) is an American businessman who co-founded [[Chef America Inc.]] that popularized the concept of microwavable frozen meals.\n\n==Biography==\nMerage was born in [[Iran]] in 1934 to a [[Iranian Jews|Jewish]] family,<ref name=LAHelp>[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/apr/01/local/me-merage1 Los Angeles Times: \"Merage Makes It His Business to Help Others - UCI's biggest donor began giving away his money after moving to Newport Beach in 2003\" by Jeff Gottlieb] April 01, 2005</ref> the son of Katherine and Andre Merage.<ref name=AndreObit>[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/27/classified/paid-notice-deaths-merage-andre.html New York Times: \"Paid Notice: Deaths Merage, Andre\"] December 27, 2001</ref> He has four siblings: Louise, Camron, Carrol, David, and Lin.<ref name=AndreObit /><ref name=Streak>[https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:jq4BIEsnUzQJ:https://www.familybusinessmagazine.com/article-download/3611+&cd=3&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us Family Business Magazine: \"A continuing streak of value creation - David Merage and his brother sold Chef America Inc., makers of Hot Pockets, to Nestl\u00e9 in 2002. He then started a private family office whose portfolio is now valued at more than $2 billion and includes philanthropy among its ventures\" by Deanne Stone] September/October 2015</ref> His father ran an import/export business in France before he was forced to flee back to Persia prior to [[World War II]].<ref name=Streak /> He attended [[Alborz High School]] in [[Tehran]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} In 1950, at the age of 16, he immigrated to the United States to attend [[Hope College]] in [[Holland, Michigan]].<ref name=LAHelp /> He later transferred to [[UC Berkeley]] where he earned a B.A. and a M.B.A.<ref name=LAHelp /> After college, he worked in succession as a marketer<ref name=Atlas>[http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-the-family-who-got-rich-with-hot-pockets-is-giving-away-their-fortune Atlas Obsura: \"How the Family Who Got Rich with Hot Pockets Is Giving Away Their Fortune - It\u2019s a lot of money.\" by Ernie Smith] May 31, 2016</ref> for nine years at General Foods, Hunt Wesson and Specialty Foods.<ref name=LAHelp /> In 1977,<ref name=Atlas /> he and his younger brother, David Merage, founded their own company called Chef America Inc., mortgaging their homes and borrowing money from their parents.<ref name=LAHelp /> Chef America started by selling frozen Belgian waffles - then unfamiliar in the United States - to restaurants as they were difficult to cook.<ref name=Streak /><ref name=LAHelp /> In 1977, the company had $12 million in sales and was the largest company in the world mass-producing frozen Belgian waffles.<ref name=Streak /> In 1983, noticing that more women were entering the workforce, he personally developed [[Hot Pockets]], a frozen food that was microwaveable and easy to eat.<ref name=LAHelp /> The product was a resounding success and they expanded the brand to Lean Pockets and Croissant Pockets.<ref name=Streak /> In October 2002, he sold Chef America to [[Nestle SA]] for $2.6 billion;<ref name=LAHelp /> at the time, the company had sales of $750 million and 1,800 employees.<ref name=Streak /> After the sale, he founded MIG Capital LLC (formerly Falcon Investment Group LLC) which managed over $1 billion in assets.<ref name=OCBJ>[http://callcenterinfo.tmcnet.com/news/2011/08/16/5709355.htm Orange County Business Journal: \"Profiles of wealthiest in Orange County\"] August 16, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011, his net worth was estimated at $1-2 billion.<ref name=OCBJ />\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2005, Merage donated $30 million to the School of Business at [[UC Irvine]], which was renamed the [[Paul Merage School of Business]] in his honor.<ref name=LAHelp /><ref>[http://jewishjournal.com/uncategorized/66702/ Jewish Journal: \"Photo Essay: L.A.\u2019s Iranian Jews repaying Alliance\u2019s generosity\" by Karmel Melamed] November 2, 2008</ref> Merage also donated $3 million to the Merage Jewish Community Center of Orange County, California.<ref>[http://www.parstimes.com/news/archive/2005/merage_uci_gift.html School receives $30 million gift and new name]</ref><ref name=LAHelp /> He is a board member and a leading donor for the [[Pacific Symphony]] and sits on the board of the Orange County Performing Arts Center.<ref name=LAHelp /> The Merage Foundation for U.S.-Israel Trade brings Israeli M.B.A. students and executives to attend seminars in the United States to learn how to market and sell to Americans.<ref name=LAHelp />\n\n==Personal life==\nMerage is a member of the University Synagogue in [[Irvine, California]].<ref name=LAHelp />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.merage.org/about-us/ Merage Foundation website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merage, Paul}}\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Iranian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Haas School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Iranian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Alborz High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Iranian Jews]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Paul Merage\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1934}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| birth_name  = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| residence   = [[Newport Beach, California]]\n| nationality = United States\n| education   = B.A. and M.B.A. [[UC Berkeley]]\n| alma mater  = [[Hope College]]\n| occupation  = Businessman\n| known_for   = Co-founder of [[Chef America Inc.]]\n| networth    = $5.0 billion (2011)\n| spouse      = Lily Merage\n| parents     = \n| children    = Michelle Janavs\n| family      = David Merage (brother)\n| website     = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Merage''' (born 1934) is an American businessman who co-founded [[Chef America Inc.]] that popularized the concept of microwavable frozen meals.\n\n==Biography==\nMerage was born in [[Iran]] in 1934 to a [[Iranian Jews|Jewish]] family,<ref name=LAHelp>[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/apr/01/local/me-merage1 Los Angeles Times: \"Merage Makes It His Business to Help Others - UCI's biggest donor began giving away his money after moving to Newport Beach in 2003\" by Jeff Gottlieb] April 01, 2005</ref> the son of Katherine and Andre Merage.<ref name=AndreObit>[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/27/classified/paid-notice-deaths-merage-andre.html New York Times: \"Paid Notice: Deaths Merage, Andre\"] December 27, 2001</ref> He has four siblings: Louise, Camron, Carrol, David, and Lin.<ref name=AndreObit /><ref name=Streak>[https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:jq4BIEsnUzQJ:https://www.familybusinessmagazine.com/article-download/3611+&cd=3&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us Family Business Magazine: \"A continuing streak of value creation - David Merage and his brother sold Chef America Inc., makers of Hot Pockets, to Nestl\u00e9 in 2002. He then started a private family office whose portfolio is now valued at more than $2 billion and includes philanthropy among its ventures\" by Deanne Stone] September/October 2015</ref> His father ran an import/export business in France before he was forced to flee back to Persia prior to [[World War II]].<ref name=Streak /> He attended [[Alborz High School]] in [[Tehran]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} In 1950, at the age of 16, he immigrated to the United States to attend [[Hope College]] in [[Holland, Michigan]].<ref name=LAHelp /> He later transferred to [[UC Berkeley]] where he earned a B.A. and a M.B.A.<ref name=LAHelp /> After college, he worked in succession as a marketer<ref name=Atlas>[http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-the-family-who-got-rich-with-hot-pockets-is-giving-away-their-fortune Atlas Obsura: \"How the Family Who Got Rich with Hot Pockets Is Giving Away Their Fortune - It\u2019s a lot of money.\" by Ernie Smith] May 31, 2016</ref> for nine years at General Foods, Hunt Wesson and Specialty Foods.<ref name=LAHelp /> In 1977,<ref name=Atlas /> he and his younger brother, David Merage, founded their own company called Chef America Inc., mortgaging their homes and borrowing money from their parents.<ref name=LAHelp /> Chef America started by selling frozen Belgian waffles - then unfamiliar in the United States - to restaurants as they were difficult to cook.<ref name=Streak /><ref name=LAHelp /> In 1977, the company had $12 million in sales and was the largest company in the world mass-producing frozen Belgian waffles.<ref name=Streak /> In 1983, noticing that more women were entering the workforce, he personally developed [[Hot Pockets]], a frozen food that was microwaveable and easy to eat.<ref name=LAHelp /> The product was a resounding success and they expanded the brand to Lean Pockets and Croissant Pockets.<ref name=Streak /> In October 2002, he sold Chef America to [[Nestle SA]] for $2.6 billion;<ref name=LAHelp /> at the time, the company had sales of $750 million and 1,800 employees.<ref name=Streak /> After the sale, he founded MIG Capital LLC (formerly Falcon Investment Group LLC) which managed over $1 billion in assets.<ref name=OCBJ>[http://callcenterinfo.tmcnet.com/news/2011/08/16/5709355.htm Orange County Business Journal: \"Profiles of wealthiest in Orange County\"] August 16, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011, his net worth was estimated at $1-2 billion.<ref name=OCBJ />\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2005, Merage donated $30 million to the School of Business at [[UC Irvine]], which was renamed the [[Paul Merage School of Business]] in his honor.<ref name=LAHelp /><ref>[http://jewishjournal.com/uncategorized/66702/ Jewish Journal: \"Photo Essay: L.A.\u2019s Iranian Jews repaying Alliance\u2019s generosity\" by Karmel Melamed] November 2, 2008</ref> Merage also donated $3 million to the Merage Jewish Community Center of Orange County, California.<ref>[http://www.parstimes.com/news/archive/2005/merage_uci_gift.html School receives $30 million gift and new name]</ref><ref name=LAHelp /> He is a board member and a leading donor for the [[Pacific Symphony]] and sits on the board of the Orange County Performing Arts Center.<ref name=LAHelp /> The Merage Foundation for U.S.-Israel Trade brings Israeli M.B.A. students and executives to attend seminars in the United States to learn how to market and sell to Americans.<ref name=LAHelp />\n\n==Personal life==\nMerage is a member of the University Synagogue in [[Irvine, California]].<ref name=LAHelp />  \n\nMerage's daughter, Michelle Janavs, was sentenced to five months in prison for her role in the [[2019 College Admissions Bribery Scandal]]. She paid bribes totaling $300,000 to get her two daughters into prestigious universities. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Demetrakakes |first1=Pan |title=Hot Pockets Heiress in Hot Water |url=https://www.foodprocessing.com/blogs/thescoop/hot-pockets-heiress-in-hot-water/ |website=Food Processing |accessdate=2/25/2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.merage.org/about-us/ Merage Foundation website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merage, Paul}}\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Iranian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Haas School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:Iranian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Alborz High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Iranian Jews]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n", "name_user": "2601:283:4300:30c0:64db:1c98:10a2:afa2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Merage"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Mary Jane Vangilder", "text_new": "{{AFC submission|t||ts=20200209055422|u=TmmEye|ns=118|demo=}}<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mary Vangilder\n| image       = MaryJane.jpg\n| imagesize   = 290px\n| caption     = Mary Vangilder, date unknown\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1911|11|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Fairmont, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| disappeared_date   = April 4, 1946\n| disappeared_place  = [[Willard, Ohio]], U.S. \n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1946|4|4}}\n| nationality = American\n| known_for   = [[Missing person]]\n| height      = 4'11 - 5'5\n| weight      = 115 - 150 lbs.\n| father   = John W. Croft\n| mother = Anna Croft (n\u00e9e Wilson)\n| \n}}\n'''Mary Jane Vangilder''' (n\u00e9e Croft) (born November 11, 1911) is a woman who abruptly disappeared from [[Willard, Ohio]] after suddenly stopping contacting her children. At the time of her disappearance, she was estranged from her husband and children. In 2018, at the request of Mary Jane\u2019s family, a [[missing person|missing person\u2019s]] investigation was finally opened after 72 years.\n\n== Background ==\nMary Jane was born in [[Fairmont, West Virginia]] on November 11, 1911 to John & Anna Croft. She was the 4th of 8 children born to the couple. Mary Jane lived in Fairmont her whole life up until 1943 or 1944, when Mary Jane suddenly moved to Ohio to work at the Shelby Air Force Depot during [[World War II]]. She married James Wesley Vangilder, a farm laborer, on January 26, 1929 in Fairmont and had 7 children with him. Mary Jane's daughter, Anna, claimed that the home was full of abuse, and that her father, James, was an alcoholic whom was quite abusive to Mary Jane. On November 23, 1945, James filed for divorce against Mary Jane and three days later he was granted the divorce.\n\n== Life in Ohio ==\n[[File:Mary_Jane_Vangilder_Air_Force_Photo.png|thumb|left|250px|Military issued photo of Mary Jane]]\n\nMary Jane moved to [[Plymouth, Ohio]] around late 1943 for unknown reasons. Her first known address in Plymouth was a rooming house at 19 Sandusky Street. Sometime before Mary Jane began working at the depot, she began living at 2 Trux Street in Plymouth, which was accross the main road from the rooming house. Mary commenced work at the Shelby Air Force Depot on March 7, 1944 as a forklift operator.\n\nAccording to the son of one of her fellow workers, William King, his father, John, would drive Mary Jane and his brothers to the depot where they worked in a [[Ford Model A (1927-31)|1928 Ford Model A]].\n\nWilliam described Mary Jane as a cheerful person whom had long dark hair that went down to her shoulders. He also recalled once when a bad snowstorm occurred and all of the workers had to walk home, including Mary Jane. Mary Jane was only wearing dress shoes and wanted to sit down and get warm, but the workers instead helped her walk.\n\n== Disappearance ==\nLittle is known about Mary Jane's disappearance, although it is known she went to dismiss her wish to divorce her husband, James Wesley Vangilder. Some sources list her date of disappearance as February 14, 1945 due to this being her last contact with family by cashing a $25.00 [[War bond|war bond]] to her daughter, Anna.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n* Cravey, E. (2020, February 9). The search for Mary Jane Vangilder, missing since 1945. Retrieved from https://www.register-herald.com/news/crime/the-search-for-mary-jane-vangilder-missing-since/article_022e391b-0838-5ec4-8805-0aa3931ab684.html\n* MISSING PERSON: The Disappearance of Mary Jane Vangilder. (2019, August 27). Mysterious WV.\n", "text_old": "{{AFC submission|t||ts=20200209055422|u=TmmEye|ns=118|demo=}}<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mary Vangilder\n| image       = MaryJane.jpg\n| imagesize   = 290px\n| caption     = Mary Vangilder, date unknown\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1911|11|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Fairmont, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| disappeared_date   = April 4, 1946\n| disappeared_place  = [[Shelby, Ohio]], U.S. \n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1946|4|4}}\n| nationality = American\n| known_for   = [[Missing person]]\n| height      = 4'11 - 5'5\n| weight      = 115 - 150 lbs.\n| father   = John W. Croft\n| mother = Anna Croft (n\u00e9e Wilson)\n| \n}}\n'''Mary Jane Vangilder''' (n\u00e9e Croft) (born November 11, 1911) is a woman who abruptly disappeared from [[Shelby, Ohio]] after suddenly stopping contacting her children. At the time of her disappearance, she was estranged from her husband and children. In 2018, at the request of Mary Jane\u2019s family, a [[missing person|missing person\u2019s]] investigation was finally opened after 72 years.\n\n== Background ==\nMary Jane was born in [[Fairmont, West Virginia]] on November 11, 1911 to John & Anna Croft. She was the 4th of 8 children born to the couple. Mary Jane lived in Fairmont her whole life up until 1943 or 1944, when Mary Jane suddenly moved to Ohio to work at the Shelby Air Force Depot during [[World War II]]. She married James Wesley Vangilder, a farm laborer, on January 26, 1929 in Fairmont and had 7 children with him. Mary Jane's daughter, Anna, claimed that the home was full of abuse, and that her father, James, was an alcoholic whom was quite abusive to Mary Jane. On November 23, 1945, James filed for divorce against Mary Jane and three days later he was granted the divorce.\n\n== Life in Ohio ==\n[[File:Mary_Jane_Vangilder_Air_Force_Photo.png|thumb|left|250px|Military issued photo of Mary Jane]]\n\nMary Jane moved to [[Plymouth, Ohio]] around late 1943 for unknown reasons. Her first known address in Plymouth was a rooming house at 19 Sandusky Street. Sometime before Mary Jane began working at the depot, she began living at 2 Trux Street in Plymouth, which was accross the main road from the rooming house. Mary commenced work at the Shelby Air Force Depot on March 7, 1944 as a forklift operator.\n\nAccording to the son of one of her fellow workers, William King, his father, John, would drive Mary Jane and his brothers to the depot where they worked in a [[Ford Model A (1927-31)|1928 Ford Model A]].\n\nWilliam described Mary Jane as a cheerful person whom had long dark hair that went down to her shoulders. He also recalled once when a bad snowstorm occurred and all of the workers had to walk home, including Mary Jane. Mary Jane was only wearing dress shoes and wanted to sit down and get warm, but the workers instead helped her walk.\n\n== Disappearance ==\nLittle is known about Mary Jane's disappearance, although it is known she went to dismiss her wish to divorce her husband, James Wesley Vangilder. Some sources list her date of disappearance as February 14, 1945 due to this being her last contact with family by cashing a $25.00 [[War bond|war bond]] to her daughter, Anna.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n* Cravey, E. (2020, February 9). The search for Mary Jane Vangilder, missing since 1945. Retrieved from https://www.register-herald.com/news/crime/the-search-for-mary-jane-vangilder-missing-since/article_022e391b-0838-5ec4-8805-0aa3931ab684.html\n* MISSING PERSON: The Disappearance of Mary Jane Vangilder. (2019, August 27). Mysterious WV.\n", "name_user": "TmmEye", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Mary_Jane_Vangilder"}
{"title_page": "17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry\n|dates= August 18, 1862, to June 10, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br>[[Battle of Chancellorsville]]<br>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br>[[Battle of Spotsylvania]]<br>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br />[[Appomattox Campaign]]\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander =\n| commander1 =Thomas Roberts\n| commander1_label =  [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] \n| commander2 =Charles B. Merrill,\n| commander2_label =[[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] \n| commander3 =George Warren West\n| commander3_label =[[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n| commander4 =William Hobson\n| commander4_label =[[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| image = IIIcorpsbadge1.png\n| caption =1st Division, III Corps\n\n}}\n[[File:17th ME Inf Position Marker.jpg|thumb|17th Maine Infantry position marker at Gettysburg National Military Park]]\n[[File:17th Maine Inf. Vols LCCN2013648710.jpg|thumb|May 3, 1864, 17th Maine. At left is the regimental band. In the front is Col. George Warren West of Portland. The photo was taken in Northern Virginia on the day the regiment broke camp to begin its summer campaign. ]]\nThe '''17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry''' was a three-year volunteer infantry regiment from southern Maine that served primarily with the Army of the Potomac in the eastern theater of the American Civil War.\n\n==Service==\nOrganized at Camp King,[[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]], and mustered in for three years' service on August 18, 1862, and was mustered out on June 10, 1865.  Recruits still liable to serve were transferred to [[1st Maine Heavy Artillery Regiment|1st Maine Volunteer Heavy Artillery Regiment]]. The regiment was one of five raised in answer to the 2 July 2, 1862, call by Lincoln for 300,000 volunteers for three years. The state of Maine's quota was 9,609.<ref name=\"Houghton\">Houghton</ref>\n\nThe regiment was recruited in southern maine from Androscoggin, Cumberland, Franklin, and York counties. As recruits entered training camp, the regiment quickly fleshed out to ten companies, A through K. Upon muster into federal service, each recruit received a federal bounty of $27.00.<ref name=\"Houghton\" /> \n\n===Detailed Service===\n\n====1862====\n* Left State for Washington, D.C., August 21. \u2014 ''Commanded by [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] Thomas Roberts''\n* Attached to Defenses of Washington to October 7, 1862<ref name=\"OoB\">{{Cite web|title = A Compilation of the Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880-1901|url =http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html |website = cdl.library.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2017-04-08}}</ref>. \n* At Upton's Hill, Va., until October 12 \u2014 ''Attached to [[Hiram George Berry|Berry]]'s 3rd Brigade, [[David B. Birney|Birney]]'s 1st Division, [[Joseph Hooker|Hooker]]'s III Corps, [[Ambrose Burnside|Burnside]]'s Army of Potomac'' \n* Edwards Ferry October 12-28. \n* Advance to Warrenton, thence to Falmouth, Va., October 28-November 22. \n* [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] December 12-15.\n** Eastern Bank of Rappahannock December 12-13\n** Fields southwest of Fredericksburg December 13-15 \u2014 ''2 men killed and 19 wounded, complimented by Gen. Berry for steadiness of the men under fire for the first time.<ref name=\"Jordan\">Jordan</ref><ref name=\"OoB\" />''\n* To winter encampment, Falmouth VA, 16 December\n\n====1863====\n\n* \"[[Mud March (American Civil War)|Mud March]]\" January 20-24 \n* Back to encampment, Camp Sickles, Falmouth, 25 January ''\u2014 Hooker takes command of Army of the Potomac, 26 January''\n* [[Chancellorsville Campaign]] April 27-May 6. \u2014 ''Attached to Hayman's 3rd Brigade, Birney's 1st Division, [[Daniel Sickles|Sickle]]'s III Corps, Hooker's Army of Potomac''  \n** The Plank Road, April 29-30 \n** [[Battle of Chancellorsville]] May 1-5. \u2014 ''Lost 113 men killed, wounded, and missing out of about 625 in action.<ref name=\"Jordan\" />''\n* Return to Camp Sickles, 6  May \u2014 ''Roberts resigned command due to illness. Relieved by [[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] Charles B. Merrill''\n* [[Gettysburg campaign|Gettysburg Campaign]] June 13-July 24<ref name=\"Houghton\" />. \u2014 ''Attached to [[R\u00e9gis de Trobriand|de Trobriand]]'s 3rd Brigade, Birney's/[[John Henry Hobart Ward|Ward]]'s 1st Division, Sickle's/Birney's III Corps, [[George G. Meade|Meade]]'s Army of Potomac. ''  \n** To Manassas. 11-16 June\n** Centerville, 17-25 June\n** Edward's Ferry, 26 June\n** To Middletown, MD, 27 June\n** To Frederick, MD, 28 June\n** To Taneytown, MD 29 June\n** T0 Emmetsburg, 30 June\n** To Gettysburg, 1 July \n** [[Battle of Gettysburg]] July 2-3. \u2014 ''As part of Sickles Corps, took position in the Union line on Cemetery Ridge north of Little Round Top around 15:00. Sickles felt the slightly higher ground forward of his placement by Meade was better ground to defend and pushed units forward several hundred yards. This put him in a situation where there was a significant gap between his left flank and Sykes' V Corps right flank. This gap made the holding of the federal line a close-run thing. The 17th as part of Birney's Division was pushed forward to occupy the stone wall at the western edge of the Wheat Field abutting the woods there. Only the intervention of the V Corps saved the II Corps from annihilation. 17th Maine saw hot and heavy action being attacked from two sides. Seven of the color bearers were shot down before the order to retreat back to Cemetery Ridge was given. The regiment retreated in good order and drove the pursuing rebels from the field with a bayonet counterattack once they reached Cemetery Ridge. Lost 132 men killed, wounded, and missing''<ref name=\"Houghton\" /><ref name=\"Jordan\" /><ref name=\"Huntington\">Huntington</ref>\n** Pursuit of Lee July 5-24. \n** [[Battle of Wapping Heights]] July 23. \n* To Sulphur Springs encampment, 25 July\n* To Brandy Station September 15\n* [[Bristoe Campaign]] October 9-22. \u2014 ''Commanded by [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] George Warren West.<ref>Promoted from Major to Colonel by governor.</ref><ref name=\"Swartz\">{{Cite web|author=Swartz, Brian  |title = The 17th Maine backstabbers, part 2|url =http://maineatwar.bangordailynews.com/2019/02/13/the-17th-maine-backstabbers-part-2/|website = maineatwar.bangordailynews.com/|accessdate = 2019-02-13}}</ref> Attached to de Trobriand's 3rd Brigade, Birney's 1st Division, [[William H. French|French]]'s III Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac''  \n** [[First Battle of Auburn]], October 13\n** [[Second Battle of Auburn]], October 14\n** [[Battle of Bristoe Station]], October 14. \n* Advance to line of the Rappahannock November 7-8<ref name=\"Houghton\" />. \n* Kelly's Ford November 7. \n* [[Mine Run Campaign]] November 26-December 2. \n** Battle of Payne\u2019s Farm<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essentialcivilwarcurriculum.com/the-mine-run-campaign.html|title=The Mine Run Campaign - Essential Civil War Curriculum|author=James K. Bryant II|date=|website=www.essentialcivilwarcurriculum.com}}</ref> November 27. ''Lost 52 men killed, wounded, and missing<ref name=\"Jordan\" />''\n** [[Battle of Mine Run]] November 28-30.\n\n====1864====\n\n* Demonstration on the Rapidan February 6-7.\n* [[Overland Campaign]] May 3-June 15. \u2014 ''Broke camp under command Colonel West, 21 commissioned officers, 5 acting officers, and 439 enlisted men.<ref name=\"Houghton\" />''\n** [[Battle of the Wilderness]] May 5-7. \u2014 ''Commanded by West/Walker/Moore.<ref>Col West seriously wounded by bullet in his right thigh 6 May. Colonel Walker of 4th Maine relieved him to command both regiments. 7 May, Birney appointed Major Moore of 99th Pennsylvania to command.</ref> Attached to [[Alexander Hays|Hays]]'<ref>Killed in action 5 May, near the junction of the Brock and Plank Roads in the Wilderness, being struck in the head by a [[Mini\u00e9 ball]].</ref>/Crocker's 2nd Brigade, Birney's 3rd Division, [[Winfield S. Hancock|Hancock]]'s II Corps, [[George G. Meade|Meade]]'s Army of Potomac.  Set up entrenchments 5 May along Brock Road. 6 May, drove enemy from Brock one mile, and retreated unmolested to Brock Road works. Repulsed several unsuccessful assaults by Longstreet's Corps. Heavy fighting along fortifications set brush on fire. Lost 24 men killed, 147 wounded and 12 missing<ref name=\"Houghton\" /><ref name=\"Jordan\" /><ref name=\"OoB\" />''\n** Laurel Hill May 8. \n** Spotsylvania May 8-9\n** Skirmishing on Po River May 10. \u2014 ''Lost 10 wounded 2 missing.<ref name=\"Houghton\" />''\n** [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]] May 11-21,  \u2014 ''Attached to Crocker's<ref>Crocker wounded 12 May.</ref>/[[Thomas W. Egan|Egan]]'s 2nd Brigade, Birney's 3rd Division, Hancock's II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac.<ref name=\"OoB\" />''\n*** Skirmishing between Po and Brock Road, May 11 \u2014 ''While erecting works, lost 2 wounded<ref name=\"Houghton\" />''\n*** \"Bloody Angle,\" Assault on the Salient, May 12. \u2014 ''With Corps, stealthily pulled at night from Union right wing to pass behind and to woods at left end of the line. At daybreak from these woods assaulted, captured, and held breast works. Sergeant Frank Haskell and Private John F Totman captured defending Confederate division commander, [[Edward Johnson (general)]]. Lost 3 killed, 41 wounded, and 10 missing.<ref name=\"Houghton\" /><ref name=\"Jordan\" /><ref name=\"OoB\" />''\n*** ''Lieutenant Colonel Merrill returned from Maine, relieved Major Moore, and took command''\n*** [[Harris Farm Engagement|Harris Farm]], Fredericksburg Road, May 19. \n** [[Battle of North Anna]] May 23-26. \u2014 ''Attacked, took, and held rebel positions to south and west overlooking North Anna river. Lost 4 killed and 17 wounded.'' \n** Line of the Pamunkey May 26-28. \n** Totopotomoy May 28-31. \n** [[Battle of Cold Harbor]] June 1-12. \u2014 ''Attached to Egan's 1st Brigade, Birney's 3rd Division, Hancock's II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac. Birney's Division anchored right wing of army. Lost 23 men<ref name=\"Houghton\" /><ref name=\"OoB\" />. On 4 June, gained 129 men transferred from 3rd Maine whose enlistment still remained. In works skirmishing until 12 May when repeating Spotsylvania move, shifted behind center and left of Army of Potomac, quietly took positions in the moonlight at new left wing.''\n** Before Petersburg June 16-19. \n* [[Siege of Petersburg]] June 16, 1864, to April 2. 1865. \u2014 ''Lost 84 men<ref name=\"Houghton\" />'' \n** [[Second Battle of Petersburg]] June 15\u201318 \u2014 ''Commanded by Captain John C. Perry<ref>June 15-16, 1864, wounded early morning of June 16</ref>/Captain Benjamin C. Pennell<ref>\nJune 16-17, killed June 17</ref>/Major Erasmus C. Gilbreath (of the 20th IN)<ref>Took command June 18</ref><ref name=\"Houghton\" />. Attached to Egan's<ref>Egan wounded 16 JUne</ref>/Madill's 1st Brigade, Birney's<ref>Birney promoted to II Corps commander, 18 June</ref>/Mott's 3rd Division, Birney's/Hancock's II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac.<ref name=\"Houghton\" /><ref name=\"OoB\" />''\n** [[Battle of Jerusalem Plank Road]] June 22-23 \n** [[First Battle of Deep Bottom]], north of the James, July 27-28. \u2014 ''Commanded by Gilbreath. Attached to de Trobriand's 1st Brigade, Mott's 3rd Division, Hancock's II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac'' \n** [[Battle of the Crater]] July 30. \u2014 ''Lieutenant Colonel Merrill takes command 31 July''\n** [[Second Battle of Deep Bottom]] August 13-20. \n*** Strawberry Plains August 14-18. \n** [[Second Battle of Ream's Station]] August 25. \n** Poplar Springs Church September 29-October 2. \n** [[Battle of Boydton Plank Road]] October 27-28.  \u2014 ''Commanded by Captain William Hobson. Attached to de Trobriand's 1st Brigade, Mott's 3rd Division, Hancock's II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac'' \n** Raid on Weldon Railroad December 7-11.\n\n====1865====\n\n* [[Battle of Hatcher's Run]] February 5-7 \u2014 ''Commanded by [[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]  William Hobson<ref>Hobson wounded April 6</ref>). Attached to Pierce's 2nd Brigade, [[Gershom Mott|Mott]]'s<ref>Mott wounded April 6</ref>)/de Trobriand's 3rd Division, [[Andrew A. Humphreys|Humphreys]]' II Corps, Meade's Army of Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n* [[Appomattox Campaign]] March 28-April 9.\n** South Side Railroad March 29. \n** Boydton Road and White Oak Ridge March 30-31. \n** Fall of Petersburg April 2. \n** Jettersville April 5. \n** Sailor's Creek April 6. \n** High Bridge April 6-7. \n** Farmville April 7. \n** Appomattox C. H. April 9. \n** Surrender of Lee and his army. \n* At Burkesville April 11-May 1. \n* March to Washington, D. C., May 1-15. \n* Grand Review May 23. \n* Mustered out at Bailey's Cross Roads June 4, 1865. \n* Recruits transferred to 1st Maine Heavy Artillery. \n* Discharged at Portland, Me., June 10, 1865.\n\n==Armament==\n[[File:NMAH-ET2012-13936.jpg|thumb|1853 Enfield rifle-musket]]\n[[File:Springfield 1861.jpg|thumb|Springfield Model 1861]]\n\nThe 17th Maine was an 1862, Army of the Potomac, three-year regiment, that greatly increased the number of men under arms in the federal army. As with many of these volunteers, initially, there were not enough [[Model 1861 Springfield Rifle|Model 1861 Springfield Rifles]] to go around so they were instead issued imported [[Pattern 1853 Enfield|British Pattern 1853 rifles]]. These were the standard rifle for the British army having performed well in the [[Crimean War]]. The Enfield was a was a .577 calibre [[Mini\u00e9 rifle|Mini\u00e9-type]] muzzle-loading [[rifled musket]]. It was used by both armies and was the second most widely used infantry weapon in the Union forces.\n\nAt Gettysburg, on the evening of 3 July, General Birney wanted to standardize the weapons in his division<ref name=\"Houghton\" />. That evening, he had the 17th and other Enfield-equipped units in his command exchange their arms for the standard muzzle-loading rifled musket of the Union Army, the [[Springfield Model 1861]] Rifled Musket. It fired a .58 inch [[Minie Ball.]] and came with a square socket bayonet. They would carry their Springfields until their end of service.\n\n==Casualties and total strength==\nThe 17th Maine enrolled 1,371 men during its existence.<ref>http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230092433/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm |date=2006-12-30 }} State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref> It lost 12 officers and 116 enlisted men killed in action or died of wounds received in battle and an additional 4 officers and 159 enlisted men died of disease.<ref>http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unmeinf1.htm Civil War Archive Website, after Dyer</ref>  31 men died in Confederate prisons.  Total fatalities for the regiment were 370.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/gettysburgorderofbattle%28union%29.htm Civilwarhome - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110603055742/http://www.civilwar.org/battlefields/gettysburg/gettysburg-history-articles/order-of-battle-aop-gettysburg.html Civil War Trust - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* {{cite book|author=Coates, Earl J., and Thomas S. Dean |title=An Introduction to Civil War Small Arms|url=https://www.amazon.com/Introduction-Civil-War-Small-Arms/dp