n Negative Role\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BIG Star Entertainment Awards]]\n|Best Television Actor (Female)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2011\n| rowspan=2|[[Gold Awards]]\n|Best Actress in Negative Role\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|Best Actress in Negative Role\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Apsara Awards]]\n|Best Actress Negative\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[BIG Television Awards]]\n| BIG Namkeen Character Female (Fiction)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|BIG Khatarnak Character Female (Fiction)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Apsara Awards]]\n|Best Actress\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|2829969}}\n* [https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/rashmi-desai/ Rashmi Desai] in [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n* {{Twitter|therashamidesai}}\n\n{{Jhalak}}\n{{Fear Factor: Khatron Ke Khiladi}}\n{{Indian Telly Award Best Negative Actress}}\n{{Indian Television Academy Award Best Lead Actress}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Desai, Rashami}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Indian soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi television]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Assamese cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Bhojpuri cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Gujarati cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Fear Factor: Khatron Ke Khiladi participants]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Muhammadmustafa505", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rashami_Desai"}
{"title_page": "\u039cClinux", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}\n{{lowercase|\u03bcClinux}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = \u03bcClinux\n| logo = \n| screenshot = Ipod linux booting kernel.jpg\n| caption = An [[iPod classic|iPod]] booting [[iPodLinux]], based on \u03bcClinux\n| website = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/ |title=uclinux.org}}\n| family = [[Embedded Linux]]\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]\n| latest_release_version = \n| latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2014|5|4}}\n| kernel_type = [[Linux kernel]]-fork\n| userland = uClinux-dist, [[uClibc]], [[BusyBox]]\n| license = \n| working_state = Current\n| supported_platforms = See [[\u03bcClinux#Supported architectures|below]]\n}}\n[[File:Linux kernel System Call Interface and uClibc.svg|thumb|300px|[[uClibc]] is a wrapper around the [[system call]]s of the [[Linux kernel]] and/or \u03bcClinux.]]\n\n'''\u03bcClinux''' is a variation of the [[Linux (kernel)|Linux kernel]], previously maintained as a [[Fork (software development)|fork]], that targets [[microcontroller]]s without a [[memory management unit]] (MMU).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclinux.org/description/|title=uClinux Description|accessdate=2007-12-31|author=D. Jeff Dionne|author2=Michael Durrant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225125038/http://www.uclinux.org/description/|archivedate=2007-12-25}}</ref> It was integrated into the mainline of development as of 2.5.46;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucdot.org/article.pl?sid=02/11/05/0324207|title= uClinux mainline Announcement|accessdate=2008-01-15|author=Greg Ungerer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071031135123/http://www.ucdot.org/article.pl?sid=02/11/05/0324207|archivedate=2007-10-31}}</ref> the project continues to develop patches and tools for microcontrollers. The homepage lists Linux kernel releases for 2.0, 2.4 and 2.6 (all of which are [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] in mainline).\n\nThe letters \"\u03bcC\" are for \"microcontroller\": the name is pronounced \"you-see-Linux\", rather than pronouncing the letter [[Mu (letter)|mu]] as in [[Greek language|Greek]].<ref name=\"uclinuxmainpage\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclinux.org/|title=\u03bcClinux|accessdate=August 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004015712/http://www.uclinux.org/|archivedate=October 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\u03bcClinux was originally created by D. Jeff Dionne and Kenneth Albanowski in 1998. Initially, they targeted the Motorola [[Freescale DragonBall|DragonBall]] family of embedded [[68k]] processors (specifically the 68EZ328 series used in the Motorola PalmPilot) on a 2.0.33 Linux kernel. After releasing their initial work, a developer community quickly sprang up extending their work to newer kernels and other microprocessor architectures. In early 1999, support was added for the Motorola (now Freescale) [[Freescale ColdFire|ColdFire]] family of embedded microprocessors. [[ARM architecture|ARM]] processor support was added later.\n\nAlthough originally targeting 2.0 series Linux kernels, it now has ports based on Linux 2.4 and Linux 2.6. The Linux 2.4 ports were forward ported from the 2.0.36 Linux kernel by Michael Leslie and Evan Stawnyczy during their work at Rt-Control. There were never any \u03bcClinux extensions applied to the 2.2 series kernels.\n\nSince version 2.5.46 of the Linux kernel, the major parts of \u03bcClinux have been integrated with the mainline kernel for a number of processor architectures.<ref>Miles Gillham [https://www.linux.com/news/uclinux-and-linux-set-merge \"uClinux and Linux set to merge\"], ''[[Linux.com]]'', November 19, 2002.</ref> \n\nGreg Ungerer (who originally ported \u03bcClinux to the Motorola ColdFire family of processors) continued to maintain and actively push core \u03bcClinux support into the 2.6 series Linux kernels. In this regard, \u03bcClinux is essentially no longer a separate fork of Linux.\n\n\u03bcClinux had support for many architectures, and forms the basis of many products, like [[Router (computing)|network routers]], security cameras, [[DVD player|DVD]] or [[Digital audio player|MP3 players]], [[Voice over Internet Protocol|VoIP]] phone or gateways, [[Image scanner|scanners]], and card readers.\n\nSupport for several of the original target architectures was dropped in 2018.<ref>Linus Torvalds [https://lkml.org/lkml/2018/4/15/201 \"Linux 4.17-rc1\"], ''[[LKML.ORG]]'', 15 April 2018.</ref> The obsolete CPU architectures set to be removed in Linux 4.17 and subsequent releases included ADI Blackfin, Etrax CRIS, Fujitsu FR-V, Mitsubishi M32R, Matsushita/Panasonic MN10300, Imagination META (Metag), and Tilera TILE.<ref>Jonathan Corbet [https://lwn.net/Articles/748074 \"Shedding old architectures and compilers in the kernel\"], ''[[LWN.net]]'', February 26, 2018.</ref>\n\n== Supported architectures ==\nThe current list includes:\n* [[Altera]] [[Nios embedded processor|Nios]]/[[Nios II]]\n* [[Amber (processor core)|Amber]] (open FPGA core)\n* [[ARM architecture|ARM]] [[ARM7TDMI]], [[ARM Cortex-M|ARM Cortex-M3/M4/M7]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Linux for ARM\u00ae Processors www.arm.com Summer/Winter 2013 Robert Boys bob.boys@arm.com System Design Division, ARM |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2014-07-17 |url=http://www.sase.com.ar/2013/files/2013/09/SASE2013-Linux-BobBoys.pdf |quote=What about Cortex-M and Cortex-R ? /../ These can run a modified version of Linux called uClinux.}}</ref> [[ARM Cortex-R]]\n* [[Lattice Semiconductor|Lattice]] [[LatticeMico32|Mico32]]\n* [[NXP]] [[Motorola 68000 series|680x0]] (Motorola/Freescale 680x0)\n* [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]] [[H8 Family|H8]]\n* [[Hyperstone]] E1/E2 (called hyLinux)\n* [[Intel i960]]\n* [[MIPS Technologies|MIPS]]\n* [[NXP ColdFire]] (Motorola/Freescale ColdFire)\n* [[NEC]] [[NEC V850E|V850E]]\n* [[Xilinx]] [[MicroBlaze]]\n\n=== No longer supported ===\nBefore Linux 4.17 the following architectures were also supported<ref> {{cite web |url=http://lkml.iu.edu/hypermail/linux/kernel/1804.0/00306.html |title=[GIT PULL] arch: remove obsolete architecture ports}}</ref>:\n* [[Analog Devices|ADI]] [[Blackfin]]\n* [[Axis Communications|Axis]] [[ETRAX CRIS|ETRAX]]\n* [[Fujitsu]] [[FR-V]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/ |title=Official website}}\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/pub/uClinux/dist/ |title=\u03bcClinux-dist, complete source distribution package}}\n* [http://sf.net/projects/uclinux/files/ \u03bcClinux at SourceForge]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324024708/http://retired.beyondlogic.org/uClinux/uClinux.htm |title=\u03bcClinux - Setting up the Development Environment}}\n* [https://github.com/AcceleratedLinux/accelerated-linux Accelerated-Linux], an actively developed continuation of \u03bcClinux-dist\n\n{{Linux kernel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:UClinux}}\n[[Category:Embedded operating systems]]\n[[Category:Embedded Linux]]\n[[Category:Lightweight Unix-like systems]]\n[[Category:ARM operating systems]]\n[[Category:Linux kernel]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}\n{{lowercase|\u03bcClinux}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = \u03bcClinux\n| logo = \n| screenshot = Ipod linux booting kernel.jpg\n| caption = An [[iPod classic|iPod]] booting [[iPodLinux]], based on \u03bcClinux\n| website = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/ |title=uclinux.org}}\n| family = [[Embedded Linux]]\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]\n| latest_release_version = \n| latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2014|5|4}}\n| kernel_type = [[Linux kernel]]-fork\n| userland = uClinux-dist, [[uClibc]], [[BusyBox]]\n| license = \n| working_state = Current\n| supported_platforms = See [[\u03bcClinux#Supported architectures|below]]\n}}\n[[File:Linux kernel System Call Interface and uClibc.svg|thumb|300px|[[uClibc]] is a wrapper around the [[system call]]s of the [[Linux kernel]] and/or \u03bcClinux.]]\n\n'''\u03bcClinux''' is a variation of the [[Linux (kernel)|Linux kernel]], previously maintained as a [[Fork (software development)|fork]], that targets [[microcontroller]]s without a [[memory management unit]] (MMU).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclinux.org/description/|title=uClinux Description|accessdate=2007-12-31|author=D. Jeff Dionne|author2=Michael Durrant|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225125038/http://www.uclinux.org/description/|archivedate=2007-12-25}}</ref> It was integrated into the mainline of development as of 2.5.46;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucdot.org/article.pl?sid=02/11/05/0324207|title= uClinux mainline Announcement|accessdate=2008-01-15|author=Greg Ungerer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071031135123/http://www.ucdot.org/article.pl?sid=02/11/05/0324207|archivedate=2007-10-31}}</ref> the project continues to develop patches and tools for microcontrollers. The homepage lists Linux kernel releases for 2.0, 2.4 and 2.6 (all of which are [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] in mainline).\n\nThe letters \"\u03bcC\" are for \"microcontroller\": the name is pronounced \"you-see-Linux\", rather than pronouncing the letter [[Mu (letter)|mu]] as in [[Greek language|Greek]].<ref name=\"uclinuxmainpage\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclinux.org/|title=\u03bcClinux|accessdate=August 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004015712/http://www.uclinux.org/|archivedate=October 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\u03bcClinux was originally created by D. Jeff Dionne and Kenneth Albanowski in 1998. Initially, they targeted the Motorola [[Freescale DragonBall|DragonBall]] family of embedded [[68k]] processors (specifically the 68EZ328 series used in the Motorola PalmPilot) on a 2.0.33 Linux kernel. After releasing their initial work, a developer community quickly sprang up extending their work to newer kernels and other microprocessor architectures. In early 1999, support was added for the Motorola (now Freescale) [[Freescale ColdFire|ColdFire]] family of embedded microprocessors. [[ARM architecture|ARM]] processor support was added later.\n\nAlthough originally targeting 2.0 series Linux kernels, it now has ports based on Linux 2.4 and Linux 2.6. The Linux 2.4 ports were forward ported from the 2.0.36 Linux kernel by Michael Leslie and Evan Stawnyczy during their work at Rt-Control. There were never any \u03bcClinux extensions applied to the 2.2 series kernels.\n\nSince version 2.5.46 of the Linux kernel, the major parts of \u03bcClinux have been integrated with the mainline kernel for a number of processor architectures<ref>Miles Gillham [https://www.linux.com/news/uclinux-and-linux-set-merge \"uClinux and Linux set to merge\"], ''[[Linux.com]]'', November 19, 2002.</ref>. \n\nGreg Ungerer (who originally ported \u03bcClinux to the Motorola ColdFire family of processors) continued to maintain and actively push core \u03bcClinux support into the 2.6 series Linux kernels. In this regard, \u03bcClinux is essentially no longer a separate fork of Linux.\n\n\u03bcClinux had support for many architectures, and forms the basis of many products, like [[Router (computing)|network routers]], security cameras, [[DVD player|DVD]] or [[Digital audio player|MP3 players]], [[Voice over Internet Protocol|VoIP]] phone or gateways, [[Image scanner|scanners]], and card readers.\n\nSupport for several of the original target architectures was dropped in 2018.<ref>Linus Torvalds [https://lkml.org/lkml/2018/4/15/201 \"Linux 4.17-rc1\"], ''[[LKML.ORG]]'', 15 April 2018.</ref> The obsolete CPU architectures set to be removed in Linux 4.17 and subsequent releases included ADI Blackfin, Etrax CRIS, Fujitsu FR-V, Mitsubishi M32R, Matsushita/Panasonic MN10300, Imagination META (Metag), and Tilera TILE.<ref>Jonathan Corbet [https://lwn.net/Articles/748074 \"Shedding old architectures and compilers in the kernel\"], ''[[LWN.net]]'', February 26, 2018.</ref>\n\n== Supported architectures ==\nThe current list includes:\n* [[Altera]] [[Nios embedded processor|Nios]]/[[Nios II]]\n* [[Amber (processor core)|Amber]] (open FPGA core)\n* [[ARM architecture|ARM]] [[ARM7TDMI]], [[ARM Cortex-M|ARM Cortex-M3/M4/M7]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Linux for ARM\u00ae Processors www.arm.com Summer/Winter 2013 Robert Boys bob.boys@arm.com System Design Division, ARM |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2014-07-17 |url=http://www.sase.com.ar/2013/files/2013/09/SASE2013-Linux-BobBoys.pdf |quote=What about Cortex-M and Cortex-R ? /../ These can run a modified version of Linux called uClinux.}}</ref> [[ARM Cortex-R]]\n* [[Lattice Semiconductor|Lattice]] [[LatticeMico32|Mico32]]\n* [[NXP]] [[Motorola 68000 series|680x0]] (Motorola/Freescale 680x0)\n* [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]] [[H8 Family|H8]]\n* [[Hyperstone]] E1/E2 (called hyLinux)\n* [[Intel i960]]\n* [[MIPS Technologies|MIPS]]\n* [[NXP ColdFire]] (Motorola/Freescale ColdFire)\n* [[NEC]] [[NEC V850E|V850E]]\n* [[Xilinx]] [[MicroBlaze]]\n\n=== No longer supported ===\nBefore Linux 4.17 the following architectures were also supported<ref> {{cite web |url=http://lkml.iu.edu/hypermail/linux/kernel/1804.0/00306.html |title=[GIT PULL] arch: remove obsolete architecture ports}}</ref>:\n* [[Analog Devices|ADI]] [[Blackfin]]\n* [[Axis Communications|Axis]] [[ETRAX CRIS|ETRAX]]\n* [[Fujitsu]] [[FR-V]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/ |title=Official website}}\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113230737/http://www.uclinux.org/pub/uClinux/dist/ |title=\u03bcClinux-dist, complete source distribution package}}\n* [http://sf.net/projects/uclinux/files/ \u03bcClinux at SourceForge]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324024708/http://retired.beyondlogic.org/uClinux/uClinux.htm |title=\u03bcClinux - Setting up the Development Environment}}\n* [https://github.com/AcceleratedLinux/accelerated-linux Accelerated-Linux], an actively developed continuation of \u03bcClinux-dist\n\n{{Linux kernel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:UClinux}}\n[[Category:Embedded operating systems]]\n[[Category:Embedded Linux]]\n[[Category:Lightweight Unix-like systems]]\n[[Category:ARM operating systems]]\n[[Category:Linux kernel]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%CE%9CClinux"}
{"title_page": "\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 single by Tarkan}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\n| cover      = Simarik.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]]\n| album      = [[Tarkan (album)|Tarkan]] & [[\u00d6l\u00fcr\u00fcm Sana (album)|\u00d6l\u00fcr\u00fcm Sana]]\n| released   = 1997\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Gramophone record|LP]]\n| recorded   = 1997\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Turkish pop music|Turkish pop]], [[dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{plainlist|\n* 3:10 (\"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" radio edit only)\n* 3:57 (original version)\n}}\n| label      = ''Urban''/''Polygram''/''[[Universal Music|Universal]]''\n| writer     = [[Sezen Aksu]], [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]]\n| producer   = Mehmet S\u00f6\u011f\u00fcto\u011flu, [[Dieter Rubach]]\n| prev_title = [[Sal\u0131na Sal\u0131na Sinsice]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[\u015e\u0131k\u0131d\u0131m]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Music album record Simarikalternate.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = CD2 single cover\n}}\n}}\n\"'''\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k'''\" ({{IPA-tr|\u0283\u026fma\u02c8\u027e\u026fk|pron}}, \"Spoilt\"), also known as \"'''Kiss Kiss'''\", is a [[1997 in music|1997]] song by Turkish singer [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]]. It was written by [[Sezen Aksu]], with music credited as composed by Tarkan. However, Tarkan later admitted in a 2006 interview that this had been done without Aksu's consent, who was the true copyright owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tarkandeluxe.blogspot.com/2006/03/tarkan-confesses.html |title=Tarkan Deluxe: Tarkan Confesses |publisher=Tarkandeluxe.blogspot.com |date=2006-03-30 |accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> It formed part of Tarkan's album ''[[\u00d6l\u00fcr\u00fcm Sana (album)|\u00d6l\u00fcr\u00fcm Sana]]''. \"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" was released in [[France]] in 1998 and the rest of the world in 1999, from the [[compilation album]] ''Tarkan'', which was released in [[Europe]]. It has sold two million copies all across Europe. Many versions of the song were recorded in different languages, most notably the English-language cover, titled \"Kiss Kiss\", by [[Greece|Greek]]-[[United States|American]] singer [[Stella Soleil]] in 2001 which was itself covered by [[Australia]]n actress [[Holly Valance]] in 2002.\n\n==The song==\nAs Tarkan's first major single, the song is generally considered his debut single. He had released three albums before this, but never released a song in single format due to the album-orientated nature of the Turkish music industry. The song has also appeared in soundtracks of various movies, including French film ''[[Beau travail]]'' and the American film ''[[XX/XY]]''. It is generally considered Tarkan's signature song in Europe. Its chorus ends with two characteristic [[kiss]] sounds.\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] is shot in Marseille, France with narrow streets and cobbled roads, with Tarkan [[singing]] and [[jaywalking]]. Several females on the streets see him and start following him to try to [[kiss]] him, but he tries to avoid them by first changing direction and then later by walking faster. More and more women begin to follow him as the song proceeds, but Tarkan eventually starts running in order to avoid them. A big group of women then run after him and as the song finishes, Tarkan takes cover in a street corner. A young girl is there as well and Tarkan kisses her [[forehead]].\n\n==Track listings==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = Single versions\n| width     = 120\n| image1    = S1 simariklp promo.JPG\n| alt1      =\n| image2    = Lpsimarik 1.JPG\n| alt2      =\n| image3    = Lp simarik3.jpg\n| alt3      =\n}}\n* ''\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k'', 1999\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Malagutti (4:46)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Malagutti edit remix (3:17)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Malagutti extended remix (7:00)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Ned Divine edit remix (3:13)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Ned Divine extended remix (5:56)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k radio edit(3:12)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k long (original) version (3:55)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Or\u0131ental (4:05)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Z\u0131o dub extended remix (6:11)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k Z\u0131o dub edit remix\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k \u015e\u0131nan soulful (6:14)\n# \u015e\u0131mar\u0131k \u015e\u0131nan dub\nTrack lists to this CD single change depending on the country of release, e.g. [[United States|America]] and Germany.\n\nThere were four promotional [[Vinyl LP|LP]] versions released.\nA promotional CD single was released in France, with an orange cover. This was the first ever release and included one track. This is now a collector's item. There was also a limited edition (fan-edition) single released in Germany, which came with a poster of Tarkan.\n\n==Commercial performance==\nWhen the single was released in Europe, it reached No. 1 in Belgium, No. 2 in Norway, plus No. 3 in Switzerland,<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?key=3894&cat=s |title=Tarkan - Simarik |publisher=swisscharts.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> France, Germany and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.top40web.nl/salestop40/jaarlijsten/jr1999.html |title=Sales Top 40 |publisher=Top40web.nl |accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> Sales went [[Gold album|gold]] in Europe, where Tarkan was presented with his gold disc at [[Cannes|Cannes Midem]] and in Germany by Universal<ref>{{cite web|title=Award for Pop Singer Tarkan|url=http://www.byegm.gov.tr/YAYINLARIMIZ/chr/ING99/10/99x10x11.HTM#%2018|publisher=Turkish Press Review|accessdate=25 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991127213631/http://www.byegm.gov.tr/YAYINLARIMIZ/chr/ING99/10/99x10x11.HTM#%2018|archivedate=27 November 1999|date=10 November 1999}}</ref> and [[Platinum single|platinum]] in [[Latin America]] where it knocked [[Enrique Iglesias]] off the top slot.\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1998\u201399)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|14|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|5|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|1|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n|Denmark ([[IFPI Denmark|IFPI]])<ref>Danish Singles Chart 17 September 1999</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|-\n|Europe ([[Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1998/MM-1998-11-28.pdf|title=Music & Media: Eurochart Hot 100|accessdate=20 June 2018|work=[[Music & Media]]}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10 \n|-\n{{singlechart|France|3|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|6|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|3|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|3|artist=Tarkan|song=Simarik|accessdate=27 June 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|2|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Portugal|19|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|3|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|3|artist=Tarkan|song=\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n!Chart (1998)\n!Position\n|-\n|Belgium (Ultratop Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=1998&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten 1998|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|Belgium (Ultratop Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=1998&cat=s|title=Rapports Annuels 1998|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5 \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n!Chart (1999)\n!Position\n|-\n|Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1999 |title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|language=German |publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]] |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|26\n|-\n|Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1999|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1999|publisher=Dutch Top 40|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1999&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1999|website=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|Sweden (Sverigetopplistan)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/43?dspy=1999&dspp=1|title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 1999|publisher=Sverigetopplistan|language=Swedish|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|24\n|-\n|Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/charts/jahreshitparade/1999|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 1999 \u2013 hitparade.ch|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Usage in media==\n\"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" was featured in films and soap opera including ''[[Beau travail]]'', ''[[Roman\u00e9]]''  and ''[[XX/XY]]''.\n\n\"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" was using with sound effect of Tarkan kiss sounds including in several Chilean television program including: ''[[Calle 7]]'', ''Yingo'', ''En portada'', ''[[Buenos D\u00edas a Todos]]'', ''[[Muy buenos d\u00edas]]'', ''[[Mucho gusto (Chilean TV program)|Mucho gusto]]'', ''Gente como t\u00fa'', ''[[La ma\u00f1ana de Chilevisi\u00f3n]]'' and others.\n\n==Stella Soleil version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Kiss Kiss\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Stella Soleil]]\n| album      = Dirty Little Secret\n| released   = April 24, 2001\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2000\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 3:01 <small>(radio edit)</small>\n| label      = [[Universal Records|Universal]]\n| writer     = Juliette Jaimes, [[Sezen Aksu]], [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]], Steve Welton-Jaimes\n| producer   = Darren Bennett, Steve Welton-Jaimes\n| prev_title = Torch\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = Pretty Young Thing\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\"'''Kiss Kiss'''\" is the debut single by American recording artist [[Stella Soleil]]. The single is a cremake of the [[Music of Turkey|Turkish]] song \"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" by [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]] with new lyrics. The English version was credited to by Juliette Jaimes, Sezen Aksu, [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]], and Steve Welton-Jaimes. The single was released to mainstream radio in April 2001. The single was also released in regions of Europe, excluding the UK.\n\n===Music video===\nThe music video is set on the beach during the late night. The video (directed by [[Hype Williams]]) shows Soleil dancing on the sand, while scenes go back and forth from birds eye views of landscape around the beach.\n\n===Track listing===\n* US promotional single<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Stella-Soleil-Kiss-Kiss/release/925156 |title=Stella Soleil - Kiss Kiss (CD) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" <small>(Radio Version)</small>\n* US 12\" promotional single<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Stella-Soleil-Kiss-Kiss/release/1503235 |title=Stella Soleil - Kiss Kiss (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" <small>(main version)</small>\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" <small>(instrumental)</small>\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" <small>(main version)</small><!-- not a mistake, it's the same version again -->\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" <small>(a cappella)</small>\n\n===Charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (2001)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|27|artist=Holly Valance}}\n|}\n\n==Holly Valance version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Kiss Kiss\n| cover      = Kiss kiss - limited edition.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Holly Valance]]\n| album      = [[Footprints (album)|Footprints]]\n| released   = 29 April 2002\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Cassette single]]\n| recorded   = 2002\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 3:23\n| label      = [[London Records|London]]\n| writer     = Juliette Jaimes, Sezen Aksu, [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]], Steve Welton-Jaimes\n| producer   = Darren Bennett, Steve Welton-Jaimes\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Down Boy]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\n\"Kiss Kiss\" is the debut recording by Australian actress [[Holly Valance]]. Her version is a remake of the 2001 song of the same name by Stella Soleil, itself a remake of \"\u015e\u0131mar\u0131k\" by [[Tarkan (singer)|Tarkan]]. The single was released in April 2002 in Australia and United Kingdom,<ref name=\"UK\"/> and shot straight to number one in both countries.\n\n===Music video===\nThe official music video for Holly Valance\u2019s version features a compilation of Valance herself with a variety of different looks and sexualised outfits whilst performing the song, all of them showed Valance wearing a violet skimpy outfit sitting on a round like chair with two disc-jockeys beside her. the second showed her dancing around red and blue neon lights, the third showed her wearing a black sparkling dress with wet hair and six male dancers dancing with her and the fourth showed Valance dancing around naked in a room full of flashing lightbulbs. There were even close-ups of Valance\u2019s lips with red sparkly lip-gloss on blowing kisses to the screen.\n\n===Commercial performance===\nThe single also debuted at number-one in the United Kingdom on 5 May 2002, selling 143,408 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"UK\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/zoom.php?id=925 |title=Holly Valance &#124; Artist |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=2014-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230124404/http://theofficialcharts.com/zoom.php?id=925 |archivedate=2009-12-30 }}</ref> The song made its debut on the Australian [[ARIA Charts]], [[UK Singles Chart]] and  [[Turkish Singles Chart]] at number one, it was Valance's first number one single. It went on to spend nine weeks in the ARIA Charts top ten, thirteen weeks in the top twenty and a total of seventeen weeks in the top fifty. In countries like [[Ireland]],  [[Finland]], [[Italy]] and [[Taiwan]] the song went to peak in the top ten. It also reached the Top 20 in [[Austria]], [[Greece]], [[Sweden]], [[Germany]], [[Japan]], [[New Zealand]], [[Switzerland]] and [[Denmark]]. It was certified Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] and Gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]].\n\n===ARIA awards===\n\"Kiss Kiss\" was nominated for four [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Awards]] at the 16th ARIA Awards in 2002.\n\n===Track listing===\n;Australian CD single\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Wise Buddha mix) \u2014 3:25\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Jah Wobble remix) \u2014 5:15\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Agent Sumo 2) \u2014 7:41\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Stargate R&B mix) \u2014 3:02\n\n;UK CD single\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Wise Buddha mix) \u2014 3:25\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Jah Wobble remix) \u2014 5:15\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Agent Sumo 2) \u2014 7:41\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Stargate R&B mix) \u2014 3:02\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (music video)\n\n;Germany CD single/UK Cassette Single\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Wise Buddha mix) \u2014 3:25\n# \"Kiss Kiss\" (Stargate R&B mix) \u2014 3:02\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|1|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|11|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss|accessdate=2010-12-08}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|28|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|12|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|20|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles|Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/00s/2002/MM-2002-05-18.pdf|title=Eurochart Hot 100 Singles|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=20|issue=21|page=8|date=18 May 2002|access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n{{singlechart|Finland|7|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|50|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|14|songid=5215|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungary|3|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss|year=2002|week=45}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|2|artist=Holly Valance}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Italy|3|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|24|year=2002|week=25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|23|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|17|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|1|date=20020511}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|12|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|19|artist=Holly Valance|song=Kiss Kiss}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|1|artist=Holly Valance|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!Position\n|-\n|Australia (ARIA)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2002.htm|title=ARIA Charts \u2013 End Of Year Charts \u2013 Top 100 Singles 2002|publisher=ARIA|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|Austria (\u00d63 Austria Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://austriancharts.at/year.asp?cat=s&id=2002|ti