       =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               =\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =\n|population_density_km2         =\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =   \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               =[[UTC+7]]\n|utc_offset             = +7\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|latd=|latm=|lats= |latNS=N\n|longd=|longm=|longs=|longEW=E\n|coordinates_type       = region:VN_type:city \n|coordinates_display    = display=inline,title \n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''\u0110\u1ed3ng S\u01a1n''' is a [[Commune-level subdivisions (Vietnam)|commune]] (''x\u00e3'') and village of [[B\u1eafc Giang]] city, [[B\u1eafc Giang Province]] in the [[Northeast (Vietnam)|Northeast]] region of [[Vietnam]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gso.gov.vn/dmhc2015/|title=Administrative subdivisions|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[General Statistics Office of Vietnam]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|location=To find information at reference, go to row 24, then row 213, and it is listed on row 07696}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bac Giang Province}}\n\n{{coord missing|Vietnam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dong Son, Bac Giang}}\n[[Category:Populated places in B\u1eafc Giang Province]]\n[[Category:Communes of B\u1eafc Giang Province]]\n{{BacGiang-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%90%E1%BB%93ng_S%C6%A1n,_B%E1%BA%AFc_Giang"}
{"title_page": "\u00d6ljait\u00fc", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Mohammed Khodabanda|Mohammed Khodabanda (Safavid Dynasty)]]}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = \u00d6ljait\u00fc<br>{{small|Muhammad Khodabandeh}}\n| image = File:Majma' al-Tavarikh 001.jpg\n| caption = \u00d6ljeit\u00fc and ambassadors from the [[Yuan Dynasty]], 1438, \"Majma' al-Tavarikh\"\n| succession = [[Ilkhanate|Ilkhan]]\n| reign = 9 July 1304 \u2013 16 December 1316\n| predecessor = [[Ghazan]]\n| successor = [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]\n| birth_date = {{death date|1282|3|24|df=y}}<ref>Linda Komaroff, ''Beyond the Legacy of Genghis Khan'' (2012), p. 19.</ref>\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1316|12|16|1282|3|24|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| issue = Bastam<br>Bayazid<br>Tayghur<br>Sulayman Shah<br>Abu'l Khayr<br>[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]<br>[[Arghun Dynasty|Ilchi]] (alleged)<br>Dowlandi Khatun<br>[[Sati Beg]]<br>Sultan Khatun\n| house = [[Ilkhanate]]\n| house-type = Dynasty\n| father = [[Arghun]]\n| mother = Uruk Khatun\n| religion = [[Buddhism]] (until 1291)<br>\n[[Christianity|Christian]] (until 1295)<br>\n[[Sunni]] (until 1310) <br>\n[[Shia]]\n|regnal name=Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad Khudabanda \u00d6ljait\u00fc Sultan|succession2=Viceroy of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]]|predecessor2=[[Ghazan]]|reign2=1296 - 1304|successor2=[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]|coronation=19 July 1304}}\n'''\u00d6ljeit\u00fc''', '''Oljeitu''', '''Olcayto''' or '''Uljeitu''', \u00d6ljaitu, \u00d6lziit ({{lang-mn|\u1826\u182f\u1835\u1821\u1822\u1832\u1826 \u183a\u182c\u1820\u1828|\u00d6ljeit\u00fc Ilkhan|}}, \u04e8\u043b\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0442 \u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d), also known as '''Muhammad Khodabandeh''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062e\u062f\u0627\u0628\u0646\u062f\u0647 - \u0627\u0648\u0644\u062c\u0627\u06cc\u062a\u0648}}, ''khod\u0101bandeh'' from [[Persian language|Persian]] meaning the \"slave of God\" or \"servant of God\"; 1280 \u2013 December 16, 1316), was the eighth [[Ilkhanate|Ilkhanid dynasty]] ruler from 1304 to 1316 in [[Tabriz]], [[Iran]]. His name \"\u00d6lziit\" means \"blessed\" in the [[Mongolian language]].\n\nHe was the son of the [[Ilkhan (title)|Ilkhan]] ruler [[Arghun]], brother and successor of [[Mahmud Ghazan]] (5th successor of Genghis Khan), and great-grandson of the Ilkhanate founder [[Hulagu]].\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:Soltaniyeh exterior.jpg|thumb|The mausoleum of \u00d6ljait\u00fc at [[Soltaniyeh]], [[Iran]].]]\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc was born as the son of [[Arghun]] and his third wife, [[Keraites|Keraite]] Christian Uruk Khatun on 24 March 1282 during his father's viceroyalty in [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]].<ref name=wives>{{cite journal|title= Christian wives of Mongol khans: Tartar queens and missionary expectations in Asia |author=Ryan, James D.|journal=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society|volume=8|number=9|date=November 1998|pages=411&ndash;421|doi=10.1017/s1356186300010506}}</ref> He was given the name Khar-banda (Mule driver)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dashdondog|first=Bayarsaikhan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HrqqhduBapQC|title=The Mongols and the Armenians (1220-1335)|date=2010-12-07|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-18635-4|location=|pages=203|language=en}}</ref> at birth, raised as [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] and later baptised in 1291<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eI19AwAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols and the West: 1221-1410|date=2014-05-01|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-87899-5|location=|pages=177|language=en}}</ref>, receiving the name Nikolya (''[[Nicholas]]'') after [[Pope Nicholas IV]].<ref>\"Arghun had one of his sons baptized, Khordabandah, the future \u00d6ljeitu, and in the Pope's honor, went as far as giving him the name Nicholas\", ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', Jean-Paul Roux, p. 408.</ref> However, according ''Tarikh-i Uljaytu'' (History of Oljeitu), \u00d6ljeitu was at first known as \"\u00d6ljeitu Buqa\", and then \"Matmodar\", and finally \"Kharbanda\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=K\u0101sh\u0101n\u012b, \u02bbAbd All\u0101h ibn \u02bbAl\u012b.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/643519562|title=T\u0101r\u012bkh-i \u016alj\u0101yt\u016b|last2=\u0643\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0646\u0649\u060c \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0644\u0649.|date=2005|publisher=Shirkat Intish\u0101rat-i \u02bbIlm\u012b va Farhang\u012b|others=Hambal\u012b, Mah\u012bn., \u0647\u0645\u0628\u0644\u0649\u060c \u0645\u0647\u064a\u0646.|year=|isbn=964-445-718-8|edition=Ch\u0101p-i 2|location=[[Tehran]]|pages=|language=fa|oclc=643519562}}</ref> Same source also mentions that it rained when he was born, and the delighted Mongols called him by the Mongolian name \u00d6ljeitu (\u04e8\u043b\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0442), meaning auspicious.  He was later converted to [[Sunni]] Islam along with his brother Ghazan. Like his brother, he changed his first name to the Islamic name ''Muhammad''.\n\nHe participated in battles involving Ghazan's fight against [[Baydu]]. After his brother Ghazan's ascession to throne, he was appointed as viceroy of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://islamansiklopedisi.org.tr/olcaytu-han|title=OLCAYTU HAN - TDV \u0130sl\u00e2m Ansiklopedisi|last=\u00d6zg\u00fcdenli|first=Osman Gazi|date=|website=islamansiklopedisi.org.tr|language=tr|trans-title=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Despite being appointed heir of Ghazan since 1299<ref>Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn \u1e6cab\u012bb, J\u0101mi\u02bf al-taw\u0101r\u012bkh, ed. Mu\u1e25ammad Raushan and Mu\u1e63\u1e6dafa M\u016bsav\u012b (Tehran: Alburz, 1994), p. 1324</ref>, after hearing news of his death he sought to eliminate potential rivals to throne. First such act was taken against Prince Alafrang, son of [[Gaykhatu]]. He was killed by an emissary of \u00d6ljait\u00fc on 30 May 1304.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/alafrank-the-eldest-son-of-the-il-khan-geikatu-r-1291-95|title=AL\u0100FRANK \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Another powerful emir, Horqudaq was likewise captured and executed.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/745412|title=The Cambridge history of Iran.|date=1968-1991|publisher=University Press|others=Fisher, W. B. (William Bayne)|year=|isbn=0-521-06935-1|location=Cambridge,|pages=397-406|oclc=745412}}</ref> \n\n== Reign ==\nHe arrived in Ujan plains on 9 July 1304<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goldhorde.ru/en/stati2018-2-12/|title=Mirza Ulugh Beg on the Chinggisids on the Throne of Iran: The Reigns of \u00d6ljait\u00fc Khan and Abu Sa\u2019id Bahadur Khan|last=Tulibayeva|first=Zhuldyz M.|date=2018-06-26|website=\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435|language=en-US|doi=10.22378/2313-6197.2018-6-2.422-438|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and was coronated on 19 July 1304<ref name=\":1\" />. Rashid al-Din wrote that he adopted the name Oljeitu following Yuan emperor [[Tem\u00fcr Khan|\u00d6ljeitu Tem\u00fcr]] enthroned in [[Khanbaliq|Dadu]]. His full regnal title was Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad Khudabanda \u00d6ljait\u00fc Sultan. Upon accession, he made several appointments, such [[Kutlushah|Qutluqshah]] to the post of commander-in-chief of Ilkhanate army, [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]] and Sa'd al-Din Savaji as his viziers on 22 July 1304. Another appointment was Asil al-Din, son of [[Nasir al-Din al-Tusi|Nasir al-Din Tusi]] as his father's successor to head [[Maragheh observatory]]. Another political decision was revoking [[Kerman]] from [[Qutlugh-Khanids|Qutluqkhanid]] [[Qutb al-Din Shah Jahan]] on 21 April same year. \u00d6ljait\u00fc appointed his father-in-law and uncle Irinjin to viceroyalty of Anatolia on 27 June 1305.\n\nHe received ambassadors from [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan Dynasty]] (19 September), [[Chagatai Khanate]] (in persons of Chapar, son of [[Kaidu]] and [[Duwa]], son of [[Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq|Baraq]]) and [[Golden Horde]] (8 December) same year, establishing an intra-Mongol peace.<ref name=\":1\" /> His reign also saw a wave of migration from Central Asia during in 1306. Certain Borjigid princes, such as Mingqan Ke'un (grandson of [[Ariq B\u00f6ke]] and grandfather of future [[Arpa Ke'un]]), Sarban (son of [[Kaidu]]), Tem\u00fcr (a descendant of [[Qasar|Jochi Qasar]]) arrived in Khorasan with 30.000<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Jackson, Peter, 1948 January 27-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/980348050|title=The Mongols & the Islamic world : from conquest to conversion|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0-300-22728-4|location=New Haven|pages=201-206|oclc=980348050}}</ref> or 50.000 followers.\n\nHe undertook an expedition to [[Herat]] against [[Kart dynasty|Kartid]] ruler Fakhr al-Din in 1306, but succeeded only briefly, his emir Danishmend was killed during the ambush. He started his second military campaign in June 1307 towards [[Gilan Province|Gilan]]. It was a success thanks to combines forces of emirs like Sutai, Esen Qutluq, \u0130rinjin, Sevinch, [[Chupan]], Toghan and Mu'min. Despite success, his commander-in-chief [[Kutlushah|Qutluqshah]] was defeated and killed during campaign, which paved way for Chupan to rise in ranks. Following this, he ordered another campaign against Kartids, this time commandered by late emir Danishmend's son Bujai. Bujai was successful after a siege from 5 February to 24 June, finally capturing the citadel. A corps of Frank [[mangonel]] specialists is known to have accompanied the Ilkhanid army in this conquest.<ref>Peter Jackson, ''The Mongols and the West'', p. 315.</ref>\n\nAnother important event of 1307 was completion of ''[[Jami' al-tawarikh|Jami al-Tawarikh]]'' by Rashid al-Din on 14 April 1307.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite thesis|title=Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn and the making of history in Mongol Iran|url=https://digital.lib.washington.edu:443/researchworks/handle/1773/23424|date=2013-07-25|degree=Thesis|language=en-US|first=Stefan|last=Kamola}} p. 204-224</ref> Later in 1307, a revolt broke in [[Kurdistan]] under leadership of certain Musa, who claimed to be [[Mahdi]].Uprising was shortly defeated.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Peacock|first=A. C. S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-qCsDwAAQBAJ|title=Islam, Literature and Society in Mongol Anatolia|date=2019-10-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-1-108-49936-1|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref>Another religious revolt, this time by 10.000 strong Christians, broke in [[Erbil|Irbil]]. Despite [[Yahballaha III|Mar Yahballaha]]'s best efforts to avert the impending doom, the citadel was at last taken after a siege by Ilkhanate troops and Kurdish tribesmen on 1 July 1310, and all the defenders were massacred, including many of the [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants of the lower town.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Brill Online|url=http://www.brillonline.nl/subscriber/uid=3277/title_home?title_id=islam_islam|title=Encyclopaedia of Islam. Second edition Second edition|publisher=Brill Online.|location=Leiden|language=English|oclc=624382576}}</ref>\n\nAn important change in administration happened in 1312 when \u00d6ljait\u00fc's vizier Sa'd al-Din Savaji was arrested on charges of corruption and executed on 20 February 1312. He was soon replaced by Taj al-Din Ali Shah who would head the Ilkhanate civil administration till 1323. Another victim of purge was Taj al-Din Avaji, a follower of Sa'd al-Din. \u00d6ljait\u00fc also finally launched a last campaign against the Mamluks same, in which he was unsuccessful, though he reportedly briefly took [[Damascus]].<ref name=\"Stevens\">Stevens, John. ''The history of Persia. Containing, the lives and memorable actions of its kings from the first erecting of that monarchy to this time; an exact Description of all its Dominions; a curious Account of India, China, Tartary, Kermon, Arabia, Nixabur, and the Islands of Ceylon and Timor; as also of all Cities occasionally mentioned, as Schiras, Samarkand, Bokara, &c. Manners and Customs of those People, Persian Worshippers of Fire; Plants, Beasts, Product, and Trade. With many instructive and pleasant digressions, being remarkable Stories or Passages, occasionally occurring, as Strange Burials; Burning of the Dead; Liquors of several Countries; Hunting; Fishing; Practice of Physick; famous Physicians in the East; Actions of Tamerlan, &c. To which is added, an abridgment of the lives of the kings of Harmuz, or Ormuz. The Persian history written in Arabick, by Mirkond, a famous Eastern Author that of Ormuz, by Torunxa, King of that Island, both of them translated into Spanish, by Antony Teixeira, who lived several Years in Persia and India; and now rendered into English.''</ref>It was when Mamluk emirs, former governor of [[Aleppo]] - Shams al-Din Qara Sonqur and governor of [[Tripoli]] - al-Afram defected to \u00d6ljait\u00fc. Despite extradition requests from [[Egypt]], ilkhan invested Qara Sonqur (now under new name - Aq Sonqur) with governorate of Maragheh and al-Afram with [[Hamadan]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Qara Sonqur was later given [[Oljath]] - daughter of [[Abaqa Khan]] on 17 January 1314.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMeanwhile relations between other Mongol realms were getting heated. The new khan of Golden Horde, [[\u00d6z Beg Khan|Ozbeg]] sent an emissary to \u00d6ljait\u00fc, renewing his claims to [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]] on 13 October 1312. \u00d6ljait\u00fc also supported the latter during [[Esen Buqa\u2013Ayurbarwada war|Chagatai-Yuan war]] in 1314, annexing Southern Afghanistan after expelling [[Qara'unas]].<ref name=\":1\" />After repelling Chagatai armies, he appointed his son [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]] to govern [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]] and [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]] in 1315 with Uyghur noble Amir Sevinch as his guardian. Another descendant of Jochi Qasar, Baba Oghul arrived from Central Asia same year, pillaging [[Khwarazm]] on his way, causing much disturbance.Upon protests of Golden Horde emissaries, \u00d6ljait\u00fc had to execute Baba, claiming he was not informed such unauthorized acts.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc's reign is also remembered for a brief effort of Ilkhanid invasion of [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]. [[Humaydah ibn Abi Numayy]], arrived at Ilkhanate court in 1315, ilkhan on his part provided Humaydah an army of several thousand [[Mongol|Mongols]] and Arabs under the command of Sayyid Talib al-Dilqandi to bring the Hijaz under Ilkhanid control. He also planned to exhume the bodies of the caliphs [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]] from their graves in [[Medina]]. However, soon after the expedition passed [[Basra]] they received news of ilkhan's death, and a large part of the army deserted. The remainder \u2013 three hundred Mongols and four hundred Arabs \u2013 were crushed by a horde of four thousand [[Bedouin]] led Muhammad ibn Isa (brother of [[Muhanna ibn Isa]]) in March 1317.<ref>al-Najm Ibn Fahd, ''[[\u00d6ljait\u00fc#CITEREF ithaf|It\u1e25\u0101f al-war\u00e1]]'', 3/155\u2013156</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nHe died in [[Soltaniyeh]] on 17 December 1316<ref name=\":1\" />, having reigned for twelve years and nine months. Afterwards, [[Rashid al-Din Hamadani]] was accused of having caused his death by poisoning and was executed. Oljeitu was succeeded by his son [[Abu Sa'id (Ilkhanid dynasty)|Abu Sa'id]]. \n\n== Religion ==\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc had been professing Buddhism, Christianity and Islam throughout his life. After succeeding his brother, \u00d6ljeitu became influenced by [[Shi'a]] theologians [[Al-Hilli]] and [[Maitham Al Bahrani]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Iran: A Chronological History |first=Saeed |last=Alizadeh|author2=Alireza Pahlavani |author3=Ali Sadrnia |page=137}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Ali |last=Al Oraibi|chapter=Rationalism in the school of Bahrain: a historical perspective|title=Sh\u012b\u02bbite Heritage: Essays on Classical and Modern Traditions |editor=Lynda Clarke|publisher=Global Academic Publishing |year=2001 |page=336}}</ref> Although another source indicates he converted to Islam through the persuasions of his wife.<ref>The preaching of Islam: a history of the propagation of the Muslim faith By Sir Thomas Walker Arnold, p. 197.</ref> Upon Al-Hilli's death, Oljeitu transferred his teacher's remains from [[Baghdad]] to a domed shrine he built in Soltaniyeh. Later, alienated by the factional strife between the Hanafis and the Shafis, Oljeitu changed his sect to Shi'a Islam in 1310.<ref>Ann K.S. Lambton, ''Continuity and Change in Medieval Persia'', ed. Ehsan Yarshater, (Bibliotheca Persica, 1988), p. 255.</ref> However, it has also been reported that he reconverted to Sunni Islam prior to his death.<ref>{{cite book|last=Curatola|first=Giovanni|title=Iran: The Art and Architecture of Persia|date=2007|publisher=Perseus Distribution Services|isbn=9780789209207|page=166|author2=Gianroberto Scarcia }}</ref> At some point, he even considered converting to [[Tengrism|Tengriism]] in early 1310.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nHe oversaw the end of construction of city of [[Soltaniyeh]]<ref name=\"Stevens\" /> on Qongqur-Oleng plains in 1306. In 1309, \u00d6ljeitu founded a ''Dar al-Sayyedah'' (\"[[Sayyed]]'s lodge\") in [[Shiraz, Iran|Shiraz]], [[Iran]], and endowed it with an income of 10,000 Dinars a year. His tomb in [[Soltaniyeh]], 300&nbsp;km west of [[Tehran]], remains the best known monument of Ilkhanid [[Persia]].\n\n==Relations with Europe==\n\n===Trade contacts===\nTrading contacts with European powers were very active during the reign of \u00d6ljeitu. The Genoese had first appeared in the capital of [[Tabriz]] in 1280, and they maintained a resident [[Consul (representative)|Consul]] by 1304. Oljeitu also gave full trading rights to the [[Venice|Venetians]] through a treaty in 1306 (another such treaty with his son Abu Said was signed in 1320).<ref name=\"Jackson, p.298\">Jackson, p. 298.</ref> According to [[Marco Polo]], Tabriz was specialized in the production of gold and silk, and Western merchants could purchase precious stones in quantities.<ref name=\"Jackson, p.298\"/>\n\n===Military alliance===\n{{see also|Franco-Mongol alliance}}\n[[File:Mongol soldiers by Rashid al-Din 1305.JPG|250px|thumb|Mongol soldiers at the time of \u00d6ljeit\u00fc, in ''[[Jami al-Tawarikh]]'' by [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]], 1305-1306.]]\n[[File:OljeituToPhilippeLeBel1305.jpg|250px|thumb|Letter of \u00d6ljeitu to Philippe le Bel, 1305. In classical Mongolian script, with the Chinese script seal of the Great Khaan in Mongolian Quadratic Script (D\u00f6rb\u00f6ljin Bichig). The huge roll measures 302x50 cm.]]\n[[File:OljeituLetterToPhilippeLeBel1305.jpg|250px|thumb|Translation of \u00d6ljeitu's message by [[Buscarello de Ghizolfi]], on the back of the letter (visible here).]]\n[[File:Ghazan et \u00d6ldje\u00eftu.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Ghazan]] and his brother \u00d6ljait\u00fc.]]\nAfter his predecessors [[Arghun]] and [[Ghazan]], \u00d6ljeitu continued diplomatic overtures with the West, and re-stated Mongol hopes for an alliance between the Christian nations of Europe and the Mongols against the Mamluks, even though \u00d6ljeitu himself had converted to Islam.\n\n====1305 embassy====\nIn April 1305, he sent a Mongol embassy led by [[Buscarello de Ghizolfi]] to the French king [[Philip IV of France]],<ref>Mostaert and Cleaves, pp. 56\u201357, [http://www.encyclopediairanica.com/articles/v10f2/v10f216a.html Source]</ref> [[Pope Clement V]], and [[Edward I of England]]. The letter to Philip IV, the only one to have survived, describes the virtues of concord between the Mongols and the Franks:\n\n{{quote|\"We, Sultan Oljaitu. We speak. We, who by the strength of the Sky, rose to the throne (...), we, descendant of Genghis Khan (...). In truth, there cannot be anything better than concord. If anybody was not in concord with either you or ourselves, then we would defend ourselves together. Let the Sky decide!\"|Extract from the letter of Oljeitu to Philip the Fair. French national archives.<ref>Quoted in Jean-Paul Roux, ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', p. 437.</ref>}}\n\nHe also explained that internal conflicts between the Mongols were now over:\n\n{{quote|\"Now all of us, [[Emperor Chengzong of Yuan China|Timur Khagan]], Tchapar, [[Tokhta|Toctoga]], Togba and ourselves, main descendants of Gengis-Khan, all of us, descendants and brothers, are reconciled through the inspiration and the help of God. So that, from Nangkiyan (China) in the Orient, to Lake Dala our people are united and the roads are open.\"|Extract from the letter of Oljeitu to Philip the Fair. French national archives.<ref>[http://www.cosmovisions.com/ChronoMongols00.htm Source]</ref>}}\n\nThis message reassured the European nations that the [[Franco-Mongol alliance]], or at least attempts towards such an alliance, had not ceased, even though the Khans had converted to Islam.<ref>Jean-Paul Roux, in ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'' {{ISBN|2-213-03164-9}}: \"The Occident was reassured that the Mongol alliance had not ceased with the conversion of the Khans to Islam. However, this alliance could not have ceased. The Mamelouks, through their repeated military actions, were becoming a strong enough danger to force Iran to maintain relations with Europe.\", p. 437.</ref>\n\n====1307 embassy====\nAnother embassy was sent to the West in 1307, led by [[Tommaso Ugi di Siena]], an Italian described as \u00d6ljeitu's ''ild\u00fcchi'' (\"Sword-bearer\").<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 173.</ref> This embassy encouraged Pope Clement V to speak in 1307 of the strong possibility that the Mongols could remit the [[Holy Land]] to the Christians, and to declare that the Mongol embassy from \u00d6ljeitu \"cheered him like spiritual sustenance\".<ref>Peter Jackson, ''The Mongols and the West'', p. 171.</ref> Relations were quite warm: in 1307, the Pope named [[John of Montecorvino]] the first Archbishop of [[Khanbalik]] and Patriarch of the Orient.<ref>Foltz, p.131</ref>\n\nEuropean nations accordingly prepared a crusade, but were delayed. A memorandum drafted by the Grand Master of the [[Knights Hospitallers]] [[Guillaume de Villaret]] about military plans for a Crusade envisaged a Mongol invasion of Syria as a preliminary to a Western intervention (1307/8).<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 185.</ref>\n\n====Military operation of 1308====\n\n[[Byzantine]] Emperor [[Andronicus II]] gave a daughter in marriage to Oljeitu and asked ilkhan's assistance against growing power of the [[Ottomans]]. In 1305, Oljeitu promised his father in law 40,000 men, and in 1308 dispatched 30,000 men to recover many Byzantine towns in [[Bithynia]] and the Ilkhanid army crushed a detachment of [[Osman I]].<ref name=\"Ian2\">I. Heath, ''Byzantine Armies: AD 1118\u20131461'', pp. 24\u201333.</ref>\n\n====1313 embassy====\nOn April 4, 1312, a Crusade was promulgated by [[Pope Clement V]] at the [[Council of Vienne]]. Another embassy was sent by Oljeitu to the West and to [[Edward II of England|Edward II]] in 1313.<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 172.</ref>\nThat same year, the French king [[Philippe le Bel]] \"took the cross\", making the vow to go on a Crusade in the Levant, thus responding to Clement V's call for a Crusade. He was however warned against leaving by [[Enguerrand de Marigny]],<ref>Jean Richard, \"Histoire des Croisades\", p. 485.</ref> and died soon after in a hunting accident.<ref>Richard, p. 485.</ref>\n\nA final settlement with the Mamluks would only be found when Oljeitu's son signed the [[Treaty of Aleppo]] with the [[Mamluks]] in 1322.\n\n==Family==\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc had thirteen consorts with several issues, albeit only one surviving son and daughter:\n*Terjughan Khatun, daughter of Lagzi G\u00fcregen (son of [[Arghun Aqa]]) and Baba Khatun\n**Dowlandi Khatun (died 1314) married on 30 September 1305 to Amir [[Chupan]]\n*Eltuzmish Khatun (m. 1296, d. 10 October 1308, buried in [[Shanb Ghazan]]), daughter of Qutlugh Timur Kurkan of the [[Khongirad]], sister of Taraqai Kurkan (widow of [[Abaqa Khan]] and previously that of [[Gaykhatu]] Khan)\n**Bastam (1297 - 15 October 1309) - married [[Uljay Qutlugh Khatun]] on 12 January 1305 (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**Bayazid (1300 - 19 April 1308) (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**Muhammad Tayfur (b. 3 December 1306) (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**[[Sati Beg]] Khatun - with Eltuzmish Khatun, married firstly on 6 September 1319 to Amir Chupan, married secondly in 1336 to [[Arpa Ke'un]], married thirdly in 1339 to [[Suleiman Khan]];\n*Hajji Khatun, daughter of Chichak, son of Sulamish and Todogaj Khatun;\n**[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan]]\n*Qutlughshah Khatun (betrothed 18 March 1305, m. 20 June 1305), daughter of [[Irinjin]],<ref>{{cite book|first=Ann K. S.|last=Lambton|title=Continuity and Change in Medieval Persia|publisher=SUNY Press|date=January 1, 1988|pages=293|isbn=978-0-887-06133-2}}</ref> and Konchak Khatun;\n**Sultan Khatun\n*Bulughan Khatun Khurasani (m. 23 June 1305, d. 5 January 1310 in [[Baghdad]]), daughter of Tasu and Mangli Tegin Khatun (widow of [[Ghazan]] Khan)\n*Kunjuskab Khatun (m. 1305), daughter of Shadi Kurkan and Orqudaq Khatun (widow of Ghazan Khan)\n*Oljatai Khatun (m. 1306, died 4 October 1315) - sister of Hajji Khatun (widow of [[Arghun Khan]])\n**Abu'l Khayr (b. 1305, died in infancy, buried next to [[Ghazan]] in [[Shanb Ghazan]])\n*Soyurghatmish Khatun, daughter of Amir Husayn Jalayir, and sister of [[Hasan Buzurg]];\n*Qongtai Khatun, daughter of Timur Kurkan;\n*Dunya Khatun, daughter of al-Malik al-Malik Najm ad-Din Ghazi, ruler of [[Mardin]];\n*Adil Shah Khatun, daughter of Amir Sartaq, the amir-ordu of Bulughan Khatun Buzurg;<ref>{{cite book|first=Robert|last=Hillenbrand|first2=A. C. S.|last2=Peacock|first3=Firuza|last3=Abdullaheva|title=Ferdowsi, the Mongols and the History of Iran: Art, Literature and Culture from Early Islam to Qajar Persia|publisher=I. B. Tauris|year=January 29, 2014|pages=131|isbn=978-1-780-76015-5}}</ref>\n**Sulayman Shah (d. 10 August 1310)\n*Despina Khatun, daughter of [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]];<ref>{{cite book|first=Dimitri|last=Korobeinikov|title=Byzantium and the Turks in the Thirteenth Century|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|pages=212|isbn=978-0-198-70826-1}}</ref>\n*Tugha Khatun, a lady accused of having an affair with [[Demasq Kaja]];\n\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc also allegedly had an additional son, Ilchi who was claimed as an ancestor of the [[Arghun dynasty|Arghun]] and [[Tarkhan dynasty|Tarkhan]] dynasties of Afghanistan and India.<ref>Mahmudul Hasan Siddiqi, ''History of the Arghuns and Tarkhans of Sind, 1507-1593'' (1972), p. 249.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hazara people]]\n* [[Olcayto]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Atwood, Christopher P. (2004). ''The Encyclopedia of Mongolia and the Mongol Empire''. Facts on File, Inc. {{ISBN|0-8160-4671-9}}.\n* ({{ISBN|0-295-98391-4}}) page 87\n* [[Richard Foltz|Foltz, Richard]], ''Religions of the Silk Road'', New York: Palgrave Macmillan, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-230-62125-1}}\n* [[Peter Jackson (historian)|Jackson, Peter]], ''The Mongols and the West'', Pearson Education, {{ISBN|0-582-36896-0}}\n* [[Jean-Paul Roux|Roux, Jean-Paul]], ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', Fayard, {{ISBN|2-213-03164-9}}\n*{{cite book|author1-last=Ibn Fahd|author1-first=Najm al-Din Umar ibn Mu\u1e25ammad|title=It\u1e25\u0101f al-war\u00e1 bi-akhb\u0101r Umm al-Qur\u00e1|date=1983\u20131984|publisher=J\u0101mi\u2018at Umm al-Qur\u00e1, Markaz al-Ba\u1e25th al-\u2018Ilm\u012b wa-I\u1e25y\u0101\u2019 al-Tur\u0101th al-Isl\u0101m\u012b, Kull\u012byat al-Shar\u012b\u02bbah wa-al-Dir\u0101s\u0101t al-Isl\u0101m\u012byah|editor1-last=Shalt\u016bt|editor1-first=Fah\u012bm Mu\u1e25ammad|edition=1st|location=Makkah|language=Arabic|script-title=ar:\u0625\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0649 \u0628\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0649|ref=CITEREF_ithaf|orig-year=Composed before 1481}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Mahmud Ghazan]]\n| title  = [[Ilkhanid Dynasty]]\n| years  = 1304&ndash;1316\n| after  = [[Abu Sa'id (Ilkhanid dynasty)|Abu Sa'id]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mongol Empire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oljeitu}}\n[[Category:1280 births]]\n[[Category:1316 deaths]]\n[[Category:Il-Khan emperors]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism from Christianity]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam from Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Converts to Shia Islam from Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire Muslims]]\n[[Category:14th-century monarchs in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Mohammed Khodabanda|Mohammed Khodabanda (Safavid Dynasty)]]}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = \u00d6ljait\u00fc<br>{{small|Muhammad Khodabandeh}}\n| image = File:Majma' al-Tavarikh 001.jpg\n| caption = \u00d6ljeit\u00fc and ambassadors from the [[Yuan Dynasty]], 1438, \"Majma' al-Tavarikh\"\n| succession = [[Ilkhanate|Ilkhan]]\n| reign = 9 July 1304 \u2013 16 December 1316\n| predecessor = [[Ghazan]]\n| successor = [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]\n| birth_date = {{death date|1282|3|24|df=y}}<ref>Linda Komaroff, ''Beyond the Legacy of Genghis Khan'' (2012), p. 19.</ref>\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1316|12|16|1282|3|24|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| issue = Bastam<br>Bayazid<br>Tayghur<br>Sulayman Shah<br>Abu'l Khayr<br>[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]<br>[[Arghun Dynasty|Ilchi]] (alleged)<br>Dowlandi Khatun<br>[[Sati Beg]]<br>Sultan Khatun\n| house = [[Ilkhanate]]\n| house-type = Dynasty\n| father = [[Arghun]]\n| mother = Uruk Khatun\n| religion = [[Buddhism]] (until 1291)<br>\n[[Christianity|Christian]] (until 1295)<br>\n[[Sunni]] (until 1310) <br>\n[[Shia]]\n|regnal name=Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad Khudabanda \u00d6ljait\u00fc Sultan|succession2=Viceroy of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]]|predecessor2=[[Ghazan]]|reign2=1296 - 1304|successor2=[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]]|coronation=19 July 1304}}\n'''\u00d6ljeit\u00fc''', '''Oljeitu''', '''Olcayto''' or '''Uljeitu''', \u00d6ljaitu, \u00d6lziit ({{lang-mn|\u1826\u182f\u1835\u1821\u1822\u1832\u1826 \u183a\u182c\u1820\u1828|\u00d6ljeit\u00fc Ilkhan|}}, \u04e8\u043b\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0442 \u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d), also known as '''Muhammad Khodabandeh''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062e\u062f\u0627\u0628\u0646\u062f\u0647 - \u0627\u0648\u0644\u062c\u0627\u06cc\u062a\u0648}}, ''khod\u0101bandeh'' from [[Persian language|Persian]] meaning the \"slave of God\" or \"servant of God\"; 1280 \u2013 December 16, 1316), was the eighth [[Ilkhanate|Ilkhanid dynasty]] ruler from 1304 to 1316 in [[Tabriz]], [[Iran]]. His name \"\u00d6lziit\" means \"blessed\" in the [[Mongolian language]].\n\nHe was the son of the [[Ilkhan (title)|Ilkhan]] ruler [[Arghun]], brother and successor of [[Mahmud Ghazan]] (5th successor of Genghis Khan), and great-grandson of the Ilkhanate founder [[Hulagu]].\n\n== Early life ==\n[[File:Soltaniyeh exterior.jpg|thumb|The mausoleum of \u00d6ljait\u00fc at [[Soltaniyeh]], [[Iran]].]]\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc was born as the son of [[Arghun]] and his third wife, [[Keraites|Keraite]] Christian Uruk Khatun on 24 March 1282 during his father's viceroyalty in [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]].<ref name=wives>{{cite journal|title= Christian wives of Mongol khans: Tartar queens and missionary expectations in Asia |author=Ryan, James D.|journal=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society|volume=8|number=9|date=November 1998|pages=411&ndash;421|doi=10.1017/s1356186300010506}}</ref> He was given the name Khar-banda (Mule driver)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dashdondog|first=Bayarsaikhan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HrqqhduBapQC|title=The Mongols and the Armenians (1220-1335)|date=2010-12-07|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-18635-4|location=|pages=203|language=en}}</ref> at birth, raised as [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] and later baptised in 1291<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eI19AwAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols and the West: 1221-1410|date=2014-05-01|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-87899-5|location=|pages=177|language=en}}</ref>, receiving the name Nikolya (''[[Nicholas]]'') after [[Pope Nicholas IV]].<ref>\"Arghun had one of his sons baptized, Khordabandah, the future \u00d6ljeitu, and in the Pope's honor, went as far as giving him the name Nicholas\", ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', Jean-Paul Roux, p. 408.</ref> However, according ''Tarikh-i Uljaytu'' (History of Oljeitu), \u00d6ljeitu was at first known as \"\u00d6ljeitu Buqa\", and then \"Matmodar\", and finally \"Kharbanda\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=K\u0101sh\u0101n\u012b, \u02bbAbd All\u0101h ibn \u02bbAl\u012b.|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/643519562|title=T\u0101r\u012bkh-i \u016alj\u0101yt\u016b|last2=\u0643\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0646\u0649\u060c \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0644\u0649.|date=2005|publisher=Shirkat Intish\u0101rat-i \u02bbIlm\u012b va Farhang\u012b|others=Hambal\u012b, Mah\u012bn., \u0647\u0645\u0628\u0644\u0649\u060c \u0645\u0647\u064a\u0646.|year=|isbn=964-445-718-8|edition=Ch\u0101p-i 2|location=[[Tehran]]|pages=|language=fa|oclc=643519562}}</ref> Same source also mentions that it rained when he was born, and the delighted Mongols called him by the Mongolian name \u00d6ljeitu (\u04e8\u043b\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0442), meaning auspicious.  He was later converted to [[Sunni]] Islam along with his brother Ghazan. Like his brother, he changed his first name to the Islamic name ''Muhammad''.\n\nHe participated in battles involving Ghazan's fight against [[Baydu]]. After his brother Ghazan's ascession to throne, he was appointed as viceroy of [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://islamansiklopedisi.org.tr/olcaytu-han|title=OLCAYTU HAN - TDV \u0130sl\u00e2m Ansiklopedisi|last=\u00d6zg\u00fcdenli|first=Osman Gazi|date=|website=islamansiklopedisi.org.tr|language=tr|trans-title=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Despite being appointed heir of Ghazan since 1299<ref>Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn \u1e6cab\u012bb, J\u0101mi\u02bf al-taw\u0101r\u012bkh, ed. Mu\u1e25ammad Raushan and Mu\u1e63\u1e6dafa M\u016bsav\u012b (Tehran: Alburz, 1994), p. 1324</ref>, after hearing news of his death he sought to eliminate potential rivals to throne. First such act was taken against Prince Alafrang, son of [[Gaykhatu]]. He was killed by an emissary of \u00d6ljait\u00fc on 30 May 1304.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/alafrank-the-eldest-son-of-the-il-khan-geikatu-r-1291-95|title=AL\u0100FRANK \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Another powerful emir, Horqudaq was likewise captured and executed.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/745412|title=The Cambridge history of Iran.|date=1968-1991|publisher=University Press|others=Fisher, W. B. (William Bayne)|year=|isbn=0-521-06935-1|location=Cambridge,|pages=397-406|oclc=745412}}</ref> \n\n== Reign ==\nHe arrived in Ujan plains on 9 July 1304<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goldhorde.ru/en/stati2018-2-12/|title=Mirza Ulugh Beg on the Chinggisids on the Throne of Iran: The Reigns of \u00d6ljait\u00fc Khan and Abu Sa\u2019id Bahadur Khan|last=Tulibayeva|first=Zhuldyz M.|date=2018-06-26|website=\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435|language=en-US|doi=10.22378/2313-6197.2018-6-2.422-438|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and was coronated on 19 July 1304<ref name=\":1\" />. Rashid al-Din wrote that he adopted the name Oljeitu following Yuan emperor [[Tem\u00fcr Khan|\u00d6ljeitu Tem\u00fcr]] enthroned in [[Khanbaliq|Dadu]]. His full regnal title was Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad Khudabanda \u00d6ljait\u00fc Sultan. Upon accession, he made several appointments, such [[Kutlushah|Qutluqshah]] to the post of commander-in-chief of Ilkhanate army, [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]] and Sa'd al-Din Savaji as his viziers on 22 July 1304. Another appointment was Asil al-Din, son of [[Nasir al-Din al-Tusi|Nasir al-Din Tusi]] as his father's successor to head [[Maragheh observatory]]. Another political decision was revoking [[Kerman]] from [[Qutlugh-Khanids|Qutluqkhanid]] [[Qutb al-Din Shah Jahan]] on 21 April same year. \u00d6ljait\u00fc appointed his father-in-law and uncle Irinjin to viceroyalty of Anatolia on 27 June 1305.\n\nHe received ambassadors from [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan Dynasty]] (19 September), [[Chagatai Khanate]] (in persons of Chapar, son of [[Kaidu]] and [[Duwa]], son of [[Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq|Baraq]]) and [[Golden Horde]] (8 December) same year, establishing an intra-Mongol peace.<ref name=\":1\" /> His reign also saw a wave of migration from Central Asia during in 1306. Certain Borjigid princes, such as Mingqan Ke'un (grandson of [[Ariq B\u00f6ke]] and grandfather of future [[Arpa Ke'un]]), Sarban (son of [[Kaidu]]), Tem\u00fcr (a descendant of [[Qasar|Jochi Qasar]]) arrived in Khorasan with 30.000<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Jackson, Peter, 1948 January 27-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/980348050|title=The Mongols & the Islamic world : from conquest to conversion|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0-300-22728-4|location=New Haven|pages=201-206|oclc=980348050}}</ref> or 50.000 followers.\n\nHe undertook an expedition to [[Herat]] against [[Kart dynasty|Kartid]] ruler Fakhr al-Din in 1306, but succeeded only briefly, his emir Danishmend was killed during the ambush. He started his second military campaign in June 1307 towards [[Gilan Province|Gilan]]. It was a success thanks to combines forces of emirs like Sutai, Esen Qutluq, \u0130rinjin, Sevinch, [[Chupan]], Toghan and Mu'min. Despite success, his commander-in-chief [[Kutlushah|Qutluqshah]] was defeated and killed during campaign, which paved way for Chupan to rise in ranks. Following this, he ordered another campaign against Kartids, this time commandered by late emir Danishmend's son Bujai. Bujai was successful after a siege from 5 February to 24 June, finally capturing the citadel. A corps of Frank [[mangonel]] specialists is known to have accompanied the Ilkhanid army in this conquest<ref>Peter Jackson, ''The Mongols and the West'', p. 315.</ref>.\n\nAnother important event of 1307 was completion of ''[[Jami' al-tawarikh|Jami al-Tawarikh]]'' by Rashid al-Din on 14 April 1307.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite thesis|title=Rash\u012bd al-D\u012bn and the making of history in Mongol Iran|url=https://digital.lib.washington.edu:443/researchworks/handle/1773/23424|date=2013-07-25|degree=Thesis|language=en-US|first=Stefan|last=Kamola}} p. 204-224</ref> Later in 1307, a revolt broke in [[Kurdistan]] under leadership of certain Musa, who claimed to be [[Mahdi]].Uprising was shortly defeated.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Peacock|first=A. C. S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-qCsDwAAQBAJ|title=Islam, Literature and Society in Mongol Anatolia|date=2019-10-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-1-108-49936-1|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref>Another religious revolt, this time by 10.000 strong Christians, broke in [[Erbil|Irbil]]. Despite [[Yahballaha III|Mar Yahballaha]]'s best efforts to avert the impending doom, the citadel was at last taken after a siege by Ilkhanate troops and Kurdish tribesmen on 1 July 1310, and all the defenders were massacred, including many of the [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] inhabitants of the lower town.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Brill Online|url=http://www.brillonline.nl/subscriber/uid=3277/title_home?title_id=islam_islam|title=Encyclopaedia of Islam. Second edition Second edition|publisher=Brill Online.|location=Leiden|language=English|oclc=624382576}}</ref>\n\nAn important change in administration happened in 1312 when \u00d6ljait\u00fc's vizier Sa'd al-Din Savaji was arrested on charges of corruption and executed on 20 February 1312. He was soon replaced by Taj al-Din Ali Shah who would head the Ilkhanate civil administration till 1323. Another victim of purge was Taj al-Din Avaji, a follower of Sa'd al-Din. \u00d6ljait\u00fc also finally launched a last campaign against the Mamluks same, in which he was unsuccessful, though he reportedly briefly took [[Damascus]].<ref name=\"Stevens\">Stevens, John. ''The history of Persia. Containing, the lives and memorable actions of its kings from the first erecting of that monarchy to this time; an exact Description of all its Dominions; a curious Account of India, China, Tartary, Kermon, Arabia, Nixabur, and the Islands of Ceylon and Timor; as also of all Cities occasionally mentioned, as Schiras, Samarkand, Bokara, &c. Manners and Customs of those People, Persian Worshippers of Fire; Plants, Beasts, Product, and Trade. With many instructive and pleasant digressions, being remarkable Stories or Passages, occasionally occurring, as Strange Burials; Burning of the Dead; Liquors of several Countries; Hunting; Fishing; Practice of Physick; famous Physicians in the East; Actions of Tamerlan, &c. To which is added, an abridgment of the lives of the kings of Harmuz, or Ormuz. The Persian history written in Arabick, by Mirkond, a famous Eastern Author that of Ormuz, by Torunxa, King of that Island, both of them translated into Spanish, by Antony Teixeira, who lived several Years in Persia and India; and now rendered into English.''</ref>It was when Mamluk emirs, former governor of [[Aleppo]] - Shams al-Din Qara Sonqur and governor of [[Tripoli]] - al-Afram defected to \u00d6ljait\u00fc. Despite extradition requests from [[Egypt]], ilkhan invested Qara Sonqur (now under new name - Aq Sonqur) with governorate of Maragheh and al-Afram with [[Hamadan]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Qara Sonqur was later given [[Oljath]] - daughter of [[Abaqa Khan]] on 17 January 1314.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMeanwhile relations between other Mongol realms were getting heated. The new khan of Golden Horde, [[\u00d6z Beg Khan|Ozbeg]] sent an emissary to \u00d6ljait\u00fc, renewing his claims to [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]] on 13 October 1312. \u00d6ljait\u00fc also supported the latter during [[Esen Buqa\u2013Ayurbarwada war|Chagatai-Yuan war]] in 1314, annexing Southern Afghanistan after expelling [[Qara'unas]].<ref name=\":1\" />After repelling Chagatai armies, he appointed his son [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Abu Sa'id]] to govern [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]] and [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]] in 1315 with Uyghur noble Amir Sevinch as his guardian. Another descendant of Jochi Qasar, Baba Oghul arrived from Central Asia same year, pillaging [[Khwarazm]] on his way, causing much disturbance.Upon protests of Golden Horde emissaries, \u00d6ljait\u00fc had to execute Baba, claiming he was not informed such unauthorized acts.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc's reign is also remembered for a brief effort of Ilkhanid invasion of [[Hejaz|Hijaz]]. [[Humaydah ibn Abi Numayy]], arrived at Ilkhanate court in 1315, ilkhan on his part provided Humaydah an army of several thousand [[Mongol|Mongols]] and Arabs under the command of Sayyid Talib al-Dilqandi to bring the Hijaz under Ilkhanid control. He also planned to exhume the bodies of the caliphs [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]] from their graves in [[Medina]]. However, soon after the expedition passed [[Basra]] they received news of ilkhan's death, and a large part of the army deserted. The remainder \u2013 three hundred Mongols and four hundred Arabs \u2013 were crushed by a horde of four thousand [[Bedouin]] led Muhammad ibn Isa (brother of [[Muhanna ibn Isa]]) in March 1317.<ref>al-Najm Ibn Fahd, ''[[\u00d6ljait\u00fc#CITEREF ithaf|It\u1e25\u0101f al-war\u00e1]]'', 3/155\u2013156</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nHe died in [[Soltaniyeh]] on 17 December 1316<ref name=\":1\" />, having reigned for twelve years and nine months. Afterwards, [[Rashid al-Din Hamadani]] was accused of having caused his death by poisoning and was executed. Oljeitu was succeeded by his son [[Abu Sa'id (Ilkhanid dynasty)|Abu Sa'id]]. \n\n== Religion ==\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc had been professing Buddhism, Christianity and Islam throughout his life. After succeeding his brother, \u00d6ljeitu became influenced by [[Shi'a]] theologians [[Al-Hilli]] and [[Maitham Al Bahrani]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Iran: A Chronological History |first=Saeed |last=Alizadeh|author2=Alireza Pahlavani |author3=Ali Sadrnia |page=137}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Ali |last=Al Oraibi|chapter=Rationalism in the school of Bahrain: a historical perspective|title=Sh\u012b\u02bbite Heritage: Essays on Classical and Modern Traditions |editor=Lynda Clarke|publisher=Global Academic Publishing |year=2001 |page=336}}</ref> Although another source indicates he converted to Islam through the persuasions of his wife.<ref>The preaching of Islam: a history of the propagation of the Muslim faith By Sir Thomas Walker Arnold, p. 197.</ref> Upon Al-Hilli's death, Oljeitu transferred his teacher's remains from [[Baghdad]] to a domed shrine he built in Soltaniyeh. Later, alienated by the factional strife between the Hanafis and the Shafis, Oljeitu changed his sect to Shi'a Islam in 1310.<ref>Ann K.S. Lambton, ''Continuity and Change in Medieval Persia'', ed. Ehsan Yarshater, (Bibliotheca Persica, 1988), p. 255.</ref> However, it has also been reported that he reconverted to Sunni Islam prior to his death.<ref>{{cite book|last=Curatola|first=Giovanni|title=Iran: The Art and Architecture of Persia|date=2007|publisher=Perseus Distribution Services|isbn=9780789209207|page=166|author2=Gianroberto Scarcia }}</ref> At some point, he even considered converting to [[Tengrism|Tengriism]] in early 1310.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nHe oversaw the end of construction of city of [[Soltaniyeh]]<ref name=\"Stevens\" /> on Qongqur-Oleng plains in 1306. In 1309, \u00d6ljeitu founded a ''Dar al-Sayyedah'' (\"[[Sayyed]]'s lodge\") in [[Shiraz, Iran|Shiraz]], [[Iran]], and endowed it with an income of 10,000 Dinars a year. His tomb in [[Soltaniyeh]], 300&nbsp;km west of [[Tehran]], remains the best known monument of Ilkhanid [[Persia]].\n\n==Relations with Europe==\n\n===Trade contacts===\nTrading contacts with European powers were very active during the reign of \u00d6ljeitu. The Genoese had first appeared in the capital of [[Tabriz]] in 1280, and they maintained a resident [[Consul (representative)|Consul]] by 1304. Oljeitu also gave full trading rights to the [[Venice|Venetians]] through a treaty in 1306 (another such treaty with his son Abu Said was signed in 1320).<ref name=\"Jackson, p.298\">Jackson, p. 298.</ref> According to [[Marco Polo]], Tabriz was specialized in the production of gold and silk, and Western merchants could purchase precious stones in quantities.<ref name=\"Jackson, p.298\"/>\n\n===Military alliance===\n{{see also|Franco-Mongol alliance}}\n[[File:Mongol soldiers by Rashid al-Din 1305.JPG|250px|thumb|Mongol soldiers at the time of \u00d6ljeit\u00fc, in ''[[Jami al-Tawarikh]]'' by [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]], 1305-1306.]]\n[[File:OljeituToPhilippeLeBel1305.jpg|250px|thumb|Letter of \u00d6ljeitu to Philippe le Bel, 1305. In classical Mongolian script, with the Chinese script seal of the Great Khaan in Mongolian Quadratic Script (D\u00f6rb\u00f6ljin Bichig). The huge roll measures 302x50 cm.]]\n[[File:OljeituLetterToPhilippeLeBel1305.jpg|250px|thumb|Translation of \u00d6ljeitu's message by [[Buscarello de Ghizolfi]], on the back of the letter (visible here).]]\n[[File:Ghazan et \u00d6ldje\u00eftu.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Ghazan]] and his brother \u00d6ljait\u00fc.]]\nAfter his predecessors [[Arghun]] and [[Ghazan]], \u00d6ljeitu continued diplomatic overtures with the West, and re-stated Mongol hopes for an alliance between the Christian nations of Europe and the Mongols against the Mamluks, even though \u00d6ljeitu himself had converted to Islam.\n\n====1305 embassy====\nIn April 1305, he sent a Mongol embassy led by [[Buscarello de Ghizolfi]] to the French king [[Philip IV of France]],<ref>Mostaert and Cleaves, pp. 56\u201357, [http://www.encyclopediairanica.com/articles/v10f2/v10f216a.html Source]</ref> [[Pope Clement V]], and [[Edward I of England]]. The letter to Philip IV, the only one to have survived, describes the virtues of concord between the Mongols and the Franks:\n\n{{quote|\"We, Sultan Oljaitu. We speak. We, who by the strength of the Sky, rose to the throne (...), we, descendant of Genghis Khan (...). In truth, there cannot be anything better than concord. If anybody was not in concord with either you or ourselves, then we would defend ourselves together. Let the Sky decide!\"|Extract from the letter of Oljeitu to Philip the Fair. French national archives.<ref>Quoted in Jean-Paul Roux, ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', p. 437.</ref>}}\n\nHe also explained that internal conflicts between the Mongols were now over:\n\n{{quote|\"Now all of us, [[Emperor Chengzong of Yuan China|Timur Khagan]], Tchapar, [[Tokhta|Toctoga]], Togba and ourselves, main descendants of Gengis-Khan, all of us, descendants and brothers, are reconciled through the inspiration and the help of God. So that, from Nangkiyan (China) in the Orient, to Lake Dala our people are united and the roads are open.\"|Extract from the letter of Oljeitu to Philip the Fair. French national archives.<ref>[http://www.cosmovisions.com/ChronoMongols00.htm Source]</ref>}}\n\nThis message reassured the European nations that the [[Franco-Mongol alliance]], or at least attempts towards such an alliance, had not ceased, even though the Khans had converted to Islam.<ref>Jean-Paul Roux, in ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'' {{ISBN|2-213-03164-9}}: \"The Occident was reassured that the Mongol alliance had not ceased with the conversion of the Khans to Islam. However, this alliance could not have ceased. The Mamelouks, through their repeated military actions, were becoming a strong enough danger to force Iran to maintain relations with Europe.\", p. 437.</ref>\n\n====1307 embassy====\nAnother embassy was sent to the West in 1307, led by [[Tommaso Ugi di Siena]], an Italian described as \u00d6ljeitu's ''ild\u00fcchi'' (\"Sword-bearer\").<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 173.</ref> This embassy encouraged Pope Clement V to speak in 1307 of the strong possibility that the Mongols could remit the [[Holy Land]] to the Christians, and to declare that the Mongol embassy from \u00d6ljeitu \"cheered him like spiritual sustenance\".<ref>Peter Jackson, ''The Mongols and the West'', p. 171.</ref> Relations were quite warm: in 1307, the Pope named [[John of Montecorvino]] the first Archbishop of [[Khanbalik]] and Patriarch of the Orient.<ref>Foltz, p.131</ref>\n\nEuropean nations accordingly prepared a crusade, but were delayed. A memorandum drafted by the Grand Master of the [[Knights Hospitallers]] [[Guillaume de Villaret]] about military plans for a Crusade envisaged a Mongol invasion of Syria as a preliminary to a Western intervention (1307/8).<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 185.</ref>\n\n====Military operation of 1308====\n\n[[Byzantine]] Emperor [[Andronicus II]] gave a daughter in marriage to Oljeitu and asked ilkhan's assistance against growing power of the [[Ottomans]]. In 1305, Oljeitu promised his father in law 40,000 men, and in 1308 dispatched 30,000 men to recover many Byzantine towns in [[Bithynia]] and the Ilkhanid army crushed a detachment of [[Osman I]].<ref name=\"Ian2\">I. Heath, ''Byzantine Armies: AD 1118\u20131461'', pp. 24\u201333.</ref>\n\n====1313 embassy====\nOn April 4, 1312, a Crusade was promulgated by [[Pope Clement V]] at the [[Council of Vienne]]. Another embassy was sent by Oljeitu to the West and to [[Edward II of England|Edward II]] in 1313.<ref>Peter Jackson, p. 172.</ref>\nThat same year, the French king [[Philippe le Bel]] \"took the cross\", making the vow to go on a Crusade in the Levant, thus responding to Clement V's call for a Crusade. He was however warned against leaving by [[Enguerrand de Marigny]],<ref>Jean Richard, \"Histoire des Croisades\", p. 485.</ref> and died soon after in a hunting accident.<ref>Richard, p. 485.</ref>\n\nA final settlement with the Mamluks would only be found when Oljeitu's son signed the [[Treaty of Aleppo]] with the [[Mamluks]] in 1322.\n\n==Family==\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc had thirteen consorts with several issues, albeit only one surviving son and daughter:\n*Terjughan Khatun, daughter of Lagzi G\u00fcregen (son of [[Arghun Aqa]]) and Baba Khatun\n**Dowlandi Khatun (died 1314) married on 30 September 1305 to Amir [[Chupan]]\n*Eltuzmish Khatun (m. 1296, d. 10 October 1308, buried in [[Shanb Ghazan]]), daughter of Qutlugh Timur Kurkan of the [[Khongirad]], sister of Taraqai Kurkan (widow of [[Abaqa Khan]] and previously that of [[Gaykhatu]] Khan)\n**Bastam (1297 - 15 October 1309) - married [[Uljay Qutlugh Khatun]] on 12 January 1305 (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**Bayazid (1300 - 19 April 1308) (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**Muhammad Tayfur (b. 3 December 1306) (named after [[Bayazid Bastami]])\n**[[Sati Beg]] Khatun - with Eltuzmish Khatun, married firstly on 6 September 1319 to Amir Chupan, married secondly in 1336 to [[Arpa Ke'un]], married thirdly in 1339 to [[Suleiman Khan]];\n*Hajji Khatun, daughter of Chichak, son of Sulamish and Todogaj Khatun;\n**[[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan]]\n*Qutlughshah Khatun (betrothed 18 March 1305, m. 20 June 1305), daughter of [[Irinjin]],<ref>{{cite book|first=Ann K. S.|last=Lambton|title=Continuity and Change in Medieval Persia|publisher=SUNY Press|date=January 1, 1988|pages=293|isbn=978-0-887-06133-2}}</ref> and Konchak Khatun;\n**Sultan Khatun\n*Bulughan Khatun Khurasani (m. 23 June 1305, d. 5 January 1310 in [[Baghdad]]), daughter of Tasu and Mangli Tegin Khatun (widow of [[Ghazan]] Khan)\n*Kunjuskab Khatun (m. 1305), daughter of Shadi Kurkan and Orqudaq Khatun (widow of Ghazan Khan)\n*Oljatai Khatun (m. 1306, died 4 October 1315) - sister of Hajji Khatun (widow of [[Arghun Khan]])\n**Abu'l Khayr (b. 1305, died in infancy, buried next to [[Ghazan]] in [[Shanb Ghazan]])\n*Soyurghatmish Khatun, daughter of Amir Husayn Jalayir, and sister of [[Hasan Buzurg]];\n*Qongtai Khatun, daughter of Timur Kurkan;\n*Dunya Khatun, daughter of al-Malik al-Malik Najm ad-Din Ghazi, ruler of [[Mardin]];\n*Adil Shah Khatun, daughter of Amir Sartaq, the amir-ordu of Bulughan Khatun Buzurg;<ref>{{cite book|first=Robert|last=Hillenbrand|first2=A. C. S.|last2=Peacock|first3=Firuza|last3=Abdullaheva|title=Ferdowsi, the Mongols and the History of Iran: Art, Literature and Culture from Early Islam to Qajar Persia|publisher=I. B. Tauris|year=January 29, 2014|pages=131|isbn=978-1-780-76015-5}}</ref>\n**Sulayman Shah (d. 10 August 1310)\n*Despina Khatun, daughter of [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]];<ref>{{cite book|first=Dimitri|last=Korobeinikov|title=Byzantium and the Turks in the Thirteenth Century|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|pages=212|isbn=978-0-198-70826-1}}</ref>\n*Tugha Khatun, a lady accused of having an affair with [[Demasq Kaja]];\n\n\u00d6ljait\u00fc also allegedly had an additional son, Ilchi who was claimed as an ancestor of the [[Arghun dynasty|Arghun]] and [[Tarkhan dynasty|Tarkhan]] dynasties of Afghanistan and India.<ref>Mahmudul Hasan Siddiqi, ''History of the Arghuns and Tarkhans of Sind, 1507-1593'' (1972), p. 249.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hazara people]]\n* [[Olcayto]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Atwood, Christopher P. (2004). ''The Encyclopedia of Mongolia and the Mongol Empire''. Facts on File, Inc. {{ISBN|0-8160-4671-9}}.\n* ({{ISBN|0-295-98391-4}}) page 87\n* [[Richard Foltz|Foltz, Richard]], ''Religions of the Silk Road'', New York: Palgrave Macmillan, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-230-62125-1}}\n* [[Peter Jackson (historian)|Jackson, Peter]], ''The Mongols and the West'', Pearson Education, {{ISBN|0-582-36896-0}}\n* [[Jean-Paul Roux|Roux, Jean-Paul]], ''Histoire de l'Empire Mongol'', Fayard, {{ISBN|2-213-03164-9}}\n*{{cite book|author1-last=Ibn Fahd|author1-first=Najm al-Din Umar ibn Mu\u1e25ammad|title=It\u1e25\u0101f al-war\u00e1 bi-akhb\u0101r Umm al-Qur\u00e1|date=1983\u20131984|publisher=J\u0101mi\u2018at Umm al-Qur\u00e1, Markaz al-Ba\u1e25th al-\u2018Ilm\u012b wa-I\u1e25y\u0101\u2019 al-Tur\u0101th al-Isl\u0101m\u012b, Kull\u012byat al-Shar\u012b\u02bbah wa-al-Dir\u0101s\u0101t al-Isl\u0101m\u012byah|editor1-last=Shalt\u016bt|editor1-first=Fah\u012bm Mu\u1e25ammad|edition=1st|location=Makkah|language=Arabic|script-title=ar:\u0625\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0649 \u0628\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0649|ref=CITEREF_ithaf|orig-year=Composed before 1481}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Mahmud Ghazan]]\n| title  = [[Ilkhanid Dynasty]]\n| years  = 1304&ndash;1316\n| after  = [[Abu Sa'id (Ilkhanid dynasty)|Abu Sa'id]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mongol Empire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oljeitu}}\n[[Category:1280 births]]\n[[Category:1316 deaths]]\n[[Category:Il-Khan emperors]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism from Christianity]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam from Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Converts to Shia Islam from Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire Muslims]]\n[[Category:14th-century monarchs in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%96ljait%C3%BC"}
{"title_page": "\u00c6bleskiver", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish traditional batter cakes}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = ''\u00c6bleskiver''\n| image            = Aebleskiver.jpg\n| caption          = \u00c6bleskiver\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Denmark\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]], [[snack]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Wheat flour]], [[buttermilk]], [[milk]] or [[cream]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sugar]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''''\u00c6bleskiver''''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8e\u02d0pl\u0259\u02ccski\u02d0w\u0250}}, [singular: ''\u00e6bleskive'']) are Danish snacks that are spherical in shape. The name literally means ''apple slices'' in [[Danish language|Danish]], although apples are not usually an ingredient in present-day versions. The crust is similar in texture to [[Europe]]an [[pancakes]], but with a light and fluffy innard like a [[popover]]. The [[English language]] spelling is usually '''aebleskiver''' or '''ebleskiver'''.\n\n==\u00c6bleskiver pan==\n[[Image:AebleskiverFront.jpg|thumb|left|Top view of an \u00e6bleskiver pan.]]\n\u00c6bleskiver are cooked on the stove top by [[baking]] in a special pan with several hemispherical indentations. The pan exists in versions for gas and electrical [[stove]]s (the latter with a plain bottom). Pans are usually made of [[cast iron]], allowing good heat retention. Traditional models in hammered [[copper]] plate exist but are today used primarily for decoration.\n\n==Preparation==\n[[File:\u00c6bleskiver.jpg|thumb|An \u00e6bleskive with red jam]]\nThe batter for \u00e6bleskiver usually includes [[wheat flour]], which is mixed with [[buttermilk]], [[milk]] or [[cream]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sugar]] and a pinch of [[salt]]. Some recipes also include [[fat]] (usually [[butter]]), [[cardamom]] and lemon [[zest (ingredient)|zest]] to improve taste, and a [[leavening agent]], most often [[baking powder]], but sometimes [[yeast]], to aerate the batter.\n\nBatter is poured into the oiled indentations and as the \u00e6bleskiver begin to cook, they are turned with a knitting needle, skewer or fork to give the cakes their characteristic spherical shape. They were traditionally cooked with bits of [[apple]] (''\u00e6ble'') or [[applesauce]] inside but these ingredients are very rarely included in modern Danish forms of the dish. \u00c6bleskiver are not sweet themselves but are traditionally served dipped in [[raspberry]], [[strawberry]], [[black currant]] or [[blackberry]] [[Fruit preserves|jam]] and sprinkled with [[powdered sugar]]. Butter, maple syrup, and whipped cream are also popular toppings.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://aebleskivers.com/history.html|title=History|website=Aebleskivers|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n\u00c6bleskiver can be bought fried and frozen at supermarkets, only needing heating in an oven.\n\n==Traditions==\n[[File:\u00c6bleskiverCook.jpg|thumb|A man making \u00e6bleskiver at the Danish American Center in Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\nIn Denmark, \u00e6bleskiver are less common in restaurants than they are at casual family gatherings. They can also be found being sold by street vendors in the winter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/la-fo-aebleskiver13-2009may13-story.html|title=All about aebleskivers|date=2009-05-13|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> They are traditionally served with jam and powdered sugar and three are placed on a plate at a time. They are traditionally eaten during the [[Christmas]] and Easter season<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.solvangrestaurant.com/about-solvang-restaurant/|title=About Solvang Restaurant|date=2016-03-08|website=Solvang Restaurant|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> and are often served with [[gl\u00f8gg]], (Scandinavian [[mulled wine]]) or Scandinavian coffee<ref name=\":0\" />. They are often sold at Christmas markets, charity markets, open-air events<ref name=\":0\" />,[[Scouting and Guiding in Denmark|Scouting functions]], local sports gatherings and similar venues. They are also served at children's birthday parties, due to their popularity and easy preparation. Voluntary associations gain profit from preparing them from the pre-fried, frozen stage and selling them, usually three at a time, with the usual condiments.\n\nIn North America there are several annual events that celebrate \u00e6bleskiver and [[Culture of Denmark|Danish culture]], with churches and museums holding \"\u00c6bleskiver Suppers\" and similar events.\n\n== History ==\nThe exact origin of \u00e6bleskiver is unknown.  One popular speculation is that a band of Vikings were part of a difficult battle.  When they returned to their ship, they wished to cook a meal similar to pancakes.  However, since they lacked regular pans, they instead used their shields or helmets, resulting in a cake with a spherical shape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.solvangrestaurant.com/about-aebleskiver/|title=About Aebleskiver|date=2017-02-10|website=Solvang Restaurant|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Paddu}}, A south Indian breakfast and evening snack.\n* {{annotated link|Puff Puff (food)}}\n* {{annotated link|List of doughnut varieties}}\n* {{annotated link|Danish cuisine}}\n* {{annotated link|Egg waffle}}\n* {{annotated link|Gai daan jai}}, a similar Chinese dish.\n* {{annotated link|Jemput-jemput}}, similar Malaysian snack.\n* {{annotated link|Kue cucur}}, similar Indonesian snack.\n* {{annotated link|List of pancakes}}\n* {{annotated link|Munker}}, the Norwegian version.\n* {{annotated link|Neyyappam}}, a similar sweet dish from Kerala used mainly as prasadam in temples.\n* {{annotated link|Paniyaram}}, a similar dish from the south of India that comes in sweet and savoury varieties.\n* {{annotated link|Poffertjes}}, a similar [[Netherlands|Dutch]] dish that is sweet.\n* {{annotated link|Popover}}\n* {{annotated link|Takoyaki}}, a savoury Japanese version that features octopus.\n* {{annotated link|Unni Appam}}, a similar dish from Kerala that is made in both sweet and spicy styles.\n*{{Portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n* [http://www.solvangrestaurant.com/about-aebleskiver/ The Story of Aebleskiver] (Solvang Restaurant, [[Solvang, California]])\n* [https://dac.mn Danish American Center], Minneapolis, Minnesota\n \n{{Pancakes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aebleskiver}}\n[[Category:Danish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pancakes]]\n[[Category:Wheat dishes]]\n{{italic title}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish traditional batter cakes}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = ''\u00c6bleskiver''\n| image            = Aebleskiver.jpg\n| caption          = \u00c6bleskiver\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = Denmark\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]], [[snack]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Wheat flour]], [[buttermilk]], [[milk]] or [[cream]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[sugar]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''''\u00c6bleskiver''''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8e\u02d0pl\u0259\u02ccski\u02d0w\u0250}}, [singular: ''\u00e6bleskive'']) are Danish snacks that are spherical in shape. The name literally means ''apple slices'' in [[Danish language|Danish]], although apples are not usually an ingredient in present-day versions. The crust is similar in texture to [[Europe]]an [[pancakes]], but with a light and fluffy innard like a [[popover]]. The [[English language]] spelling is usually '''aebleskiver''' or '''ebleskiver'''.\n\n==\u00c6bleskiver pan==\n[[Image:AebleskiverFront.jpg|thumb|left|Top view of an \u00e6bleskiver pan.]]\n\u00c6bleskiver are cooked on the stove top by [[baking]] in a special pan with several hemispherical indentations. The pan exists in versions for